# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-writers-association-of-america
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The **1994–95 Major League Baseball strike** was the eighth and longest work stoppage in Major League Baseball (MLB) history, as well as the fourth in-season work stoppage in 22 years.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike began on August 12, 1994, and resulted in the remainder of that season, including the postseason and the World Series, being canceled.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This was the first time in ninety years, since 1904, that a World Series was not played.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike was suspended on April 2, 1995, after 232 days, making it the longest such stoppage in MLB history and the longest work stoppage in a major professional sports league at the time (breaking the record set by the 1981 strike, also in MLB).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] As a result of the strike, a total of 948 games were canceled.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Both the 1994 and 1995 seasons were not played to a complete 162 games; the strike began after the teams had played at least 113 games in 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Each team played a total of 144 games in 1995.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This was the first time in North American professional sports that an entire postseason was canceled because of labor disputes; the second (and most recent) was the cancellation of the National Hockey League's 2005 Stanley Cup playoffs as a result of the entire 2004–05 season being canceled.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Coincidentally, the NHL also experienced a labor dispute of their own in 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In response to a worsening financial situation in baseball, the owners of Major League Baseball teams collectively proposed a salary cap to their players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Ownership claimed that small-market clubs would fall by the wayside unless teams agreed to share local broadcasting revenues (to increase equity among the teams) and enact a salary cap, a proposal that the players adamantly opposed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 18, 1994, the owners approved a new revenue-sharing plan keyed to a salary cap, which required the players' approval.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The following day, the owners amended the Major League agreement by giving complete power to the commissioner on labor negotiations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The dispute was played out with a backdrop of years of hostility and mistrust between the two sides.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] What arguably stood in the way of a compromise settlement was the absence of an official commissioner ever since the owners forced Fay Vincent to resign in September 1992.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This reduced trust between players and owners.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Owner representative Richard Ravitch officially unveiled the ownership proposal on June 14, 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The proposal would guarantee a record $1 billion in salary and benefits.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] But the ownership proposal also would have forced clubs to fit their payrolls into a more evenly based structure.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Salary arbitration would have been eliminated, free agency would begin after four years rather than six, and owners would have retained the right to keep a four- or five-year player by matching his best offer.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Owners claimed that their proposal would raise average salaries from $1.2 million in 1994 to $2.6 million by 2001.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fehr rejected the offer from the owners on July 18.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] He believed a salary cap was simply a way for owners to clean up their own disparity problems with no benefit to the players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On July 13, Fehr said if serious negotiations between the players and the owners did not begin soon, the players could go out on strike in September of that year, threatening the postseason.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 31, 1993, Major League Baseball's collective bargaining agreement ran out with no new agreement yet signed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] As negotiations continued to heat up, the owners decided to withhold $7.8 million that they were required to pay per previous agreement into the players' pension and benefit plans.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The final straw came on June 23 when the Senate Judiciary Committee failed to approve an antitrust legislation by a vote of 10–7.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] According to Fehr, the action left the players with little choice but to strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] "We felt in '94 we were pushed into it," he said.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On July 28, the Players Association executive board set August 12, 1994, as a strike date.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] When that day came, the players went ahead with their threat to walk off the job.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The last games of that baseball season were played on August 11, 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On August 31, three-and-a-half hours of negotiations with federal mediators produced no progress in the strike, and no further talks were scheduled as the strike went into its 4th week.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] According to then-acting commissioner Bud Selig, September 9 was the tentative deadline for canceling the rest of the season if no agreement was reached between the owners and players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The MLBPA offered a counterproposal to ownership on September 8 calling for a two-percent tax on the 16 franchises with the highest payrolls to be divided among the other 12 clubs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Teams in both leagues would share 25% of all gate receipts under the MLBPA's plan.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The owners responded by claiming that the measures wouldn't meet the cost.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The rest of the season, including the World Series, was called off by Selig on September 14.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Selig acknowledged that the strike had torn an irreparable hole in the game's fabric.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The move to cancel the rest of the season meant the loss of $580 million in ownership revenue and $230 million in player salaries.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In 1994, the average MLB salary was an estimated $1.2 million.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Montreal Expos were enjoying the best season in their history at the time of the strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Expos had the best record in baseball, 74–40, and were six games ahead of the Atlanta Braves in the NL East despite having the second-lowest payroll in MLB.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Most baseball writers considered the Expos to be World Series contenders.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Coincidentally, the only time that the Expos had made it to the postseason was in 1981, the last time that there was a significant players' strike in Major League Baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] That year, Montreal had qualified by winning the second half of the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike also cost Matt Williams of the San Francisco Giants a chance to beat Roger Maris' single season home run record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] When the strike forced the cancellation of the remaining 47 games of the season, Williams had already hit 43 home runs, on pace to match Maris' single season record of 61 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Cleveland Indians second baseman Carlos Baerga was unable to extend his record two-year streak of 20 home runs, 200 hits, and 100 RBIs by a second baseman because of the strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] By the third day of the strike, Cleveland Indians owner Richard Jacobs directed that all souvenirs being sold at the Indians' gift shop carrying the words "inaugural season at Jacobs Field" be sold at half price.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Colorado Rockies were completing their last season at Mile High Stadium with an attendance of 3,281,511 through 57 home games for an average of 57,570 per game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] At that pace, the team would have had a good chance of drawing over 4.6 million fans in their 81 home games if the season had continued.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This would have eclipsed the major league season attendance record of 4,483,350 fans set by the Rockies only the season before.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike meant that fans would not witness what was described as "one of the worst division races in history." The Texas Rangers were leading the newly reformed AL West despite being 10 games under .500.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The last-place California Angels were only 5+1⁄2 games out despite having the second-worst record in the majors at 21 games under .500—on pace for 96 losses.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In fact, the two last place teams in the other American League divisions (namely, the Detroit Tigers of the AL East and Milwaukee Brewers of the AL Central) had better records than the Rangers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The National League's MVP award was given to Jeff Bagwell.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] His hand was broken by a pitch on August 10, just before the players' strike began; had the season continued, he would likely have missed the remainder of the year and might not have won the MVP.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] But because of the timing of his "lucky break", Bagwell became just the fourth player in National League history to win the award unanimously.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike caused a transaction to take an absurd turn.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Minnesota Twins traded Dave Winfield to the Cleveland Indians for a player to be named later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Since the strike led to the season being canceled, no further transactions could be made until it was settled.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Twins would officially be listed as having sold Winfield to the Indians, but the actual transaction was conducted much differently.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Instead of the Indians buying the contract outright, team management went out for a meal with Twins management and the Indians paid the tab; this essentially meant that Winfield had been traded for dinner.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Arguably, the biggest storyline of the strike was the New York Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Yankees had not been in the postseason since 1981.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Because the Yankees' prior postseason chances had also been cut short by a strike, news media reported on the parallels between the two Yankee teams (1981 and 1994), both of which had division leads taken away by strike actions.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] MLB Baseball would not attempt another salary cap until the 2026 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 5, it was announced Richard Ravitch would step down as negotiator for the owners on December 31, 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Ravitch instead resigned on December 6, 1994.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 14, labor talks headed by federal mediator William Usery broke down.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The next day, the owners approved a salary cap plan by a vote of 25–3, but agreed to delay implementing it so that another round of talks with the players could be held.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On December 23, with negotiations at a standstill, the owners unilaterally implemented a salary cap.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 4, 1995, five bills aimed at ending the baseball strike were introduced into Congress.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The next day, Fehr declared all 895 unsigned Major League players to be free agents in response to unilateral contract changes made by the owners.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 10, arbitrator Thomas Roberts awarded 11 players a total of almost $10 million as a result of collusion charges brought against the owners.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On January 26, both players and owners were ordered by President Bill Clinton to resume bargaining and reach an agreement by February 6.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Unfortunately, President Clinton's deadline came and went with no resolution of the strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Just five days earlier, the owners agreed to revoke the salary cap and return to the old agreement.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] After the deadline passed with no compromises, the use of replacement players for spring training and regular season games was approved by baseball's executive council on January 13.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Replacement players were guaranteed $5,000 for reporting to spring training and another $5,000 if they made the Opening Day roster.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 14, the players' union announced that it would not settle the strike if replacement players were used in regular season games, and if results were not voided.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Detroit Tigers manager Sparky Anderson was put on an involuntary leave of absence as he refused to manage replacement players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] He retired soon after the 1995 season ended, disillusioned with the state of the sport.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Replacement players created major issues for two American League teams.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Toronto Blue Jays could not play games with replacement players or umpires in Ontario, due to labour code amendments passed by the Ontarian Government that prohibited replacement workers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Manager Cito Gaston and his coaching staff were sent to work with minor league players, and the team announced that games featuring replacement workers would be played at their spring training facility in Dunedin, Florida.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Baltimore Orioles, owned by labor lawyer Peter Angelos, announced they would also not be using replacement players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 20, the Orioles canceled the remainder of their spring training games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 28, Maryland governor Parris Glendening signed a law barring teams playing at Camden Yards from using replacement players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 24, Atlanta Braves replacement pitcher Dave Shotkoski was shot and killed near the team hotel in West Palm Beach, Florida.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fellow replacement player Terry Blocker assisted police in locating the suspect, who was later convicted of second-degree murder.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 26, MLB announced that the 1995 season would be reduced from 162 games per team to 144 games per team as a result of the use of replacement players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Following the end of the 1993 season, CBS Sports lost the rights to broadcast baseball games on television.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Production of nationally televised games was taken over by MLB itself, which sold the games as brokered programming to ABC and NBC as part of a joint venture that was referred to as The Baseball Network.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Originally, the idea was for ABC and NBC to share a slate of games aired in prime time during the week, with the two networks alternating coverage of the All-Star Game and World Series and splitting the Division and League Championship Series between them.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike, however, resulted in ABC losing out on two weeks of coverage and the World Series and NBC losing out on all of its allotted regular season games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] MLB and the local NBC and ABC stations lost a combined $595 million in advertising revenue, and both networks announced that they would be opting out of the deal after the shortened 1995 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Both networks would share coverage of the World Series that year, with ABC airing the odd numbered games and NBC the even numbered games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Fox became the new broadcast partner for MLB in 1996 and has remained as such since.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] NBC did elect to retain some broadcast rights; however, it continued to air the All-Star Game in even numbered years and retained its rights to air the World Series in odd numbered years until Fox gained exclusive rights to national MLB broadcasts in 2001.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On March 29, 1995, the players voted to return to work if a U.S.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] District Court judge supported the National Labor Relations Board's unfair labor practices complaint against the owners, which was filed on March 27.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] By a vote of 26–2, owners supported the use of replacement players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Judge (and future Supreme Court Justice) Sonia Sotomayor of the U.S.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] District Court for the Southern District of New York issued a preliminary injunction against the owners on March 31.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On April 2, the day before the season was scheduled to start with the replacement players, the strike came to an official end at 232 days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Judge Sotomayor's decision received support from a panel of the Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit, which denied the owners' request to stay the ruling.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] During the first days of the 1995 season, some fans remained irate at both players and owners.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Attendance at the games plummeted, as did television ratings, to a greater extent than during the last significant players' strike in 1981.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] While a total of 50,010,016 fans had attended the 1,600 MLB regular season games played in 1994, averaging 31,256 per game, a total of 50,416,880 fans attended the 2,016 games of the 1995 MLB regular season, for an average attendance of just 25,008 per game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] This represented a decline in average attendance of 20% from 1994 to 1995.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] A few of the fans who showed up demonstrated their frustration, and booed the players; the strike was seen as the worst work stoppage in sports history, leaving the game in crisis and some fans angry.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Writer Chuck Klosterman observed that during previous strikes, public anger was directed most fervently at players, but the 1994 strike attracted outrage at both players and owners in apparently equal measure.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The opening games were played with replacement umpires, the first time since Opening Day 1991 that replacement umpires were used.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On August 3, 1995, the Senate Judiciary Committee sent a bill calling for the partial repeal of baseball's antitrust exemption to the full Senate on a 9–8 vote.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In August, George Nicolau, baseball's arbitrator since 1986, was fired by the owners.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] On September 29, a three-judge panel in New York voted unanimously to uphold the injunction that brought the end to the strike in April.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The owners had appealed the injunction issued on March 31, but the panel said the Players Relations Committee had illegally attempted to eliminate free agency and salary arbitration.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The affected players include Shane Spencer of the 1998, 1999, and 2000 New York Yankees; Damian Miller of the 2001 Arizona Diamondbacks; Brendan Donnelly of the 2002 Anaheim Angels; Kevin Millar and Brian Daubach of the 2004 Boston Red Sox; and Jamie Walker of the 2006 Detroit Tigers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] Arguably the largest impact was to the Montreal Expos.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The strike was considered to be the start of the franchise's downfall in Montreal, eventually leading MLB to relocate them to Washington, D.C., to become the current Washington Nationals.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] The Expos were one of the league's top teams, and had the best record in MLB, and were six games ahead of the Atlanta Braves in the NL East.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] In 1995, they were forced to lower payroll and sell off their four highest-paid stars (Marquis Grissom, Ken Hill, Larry Walker, and John Wetteland) in the span of less than a week in spring training.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] With the strike negatively affecting its fan base, the Expos would never recover from the incident.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/1994-95-major-league-baseball-strike] After the 1994–95 strike, players' strikes became less common, although major professional sports leagues have seen lockouts amidst labor disputes between owners and players' unions.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Elections to the Baseball Hall of Fame for 2026 were conducted according to the rules most recently amended in 2022.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] As in the past, the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA) voted by mail to select from a ballot of recently retired players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The results were announced on January 20.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Two candidates were inducted by the BBWAA: Carlos Beltrán and Andruw Jones.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Beltrán was inducted in his fourth year of eligibility, and Jones was in his ninth year of eligibility.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Jones received 7.3% of the vote in his first year on the ballot in 2018, the lowest first-year percentage ever for a candidate eventually voted in by the BBWAA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A meeting of the Contemporary Baseball Era committee—one of a group of three rotating bodies generally referred to as the Veterans Committee and whose structure was amended in April 2022—was held in December 2025 to consider players from the era after 1980 who no longer appear on the BBWAA ballot.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Jeff Kent was elected from the Veterans Committee ballot.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The new inductees are scheduled to be honored in a ceremony in Cooperstown, New York, on July 26, 2026.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The list of players appearing on the BBWAA ballot was released on November 17, 2025.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] There were 15 players carried over from the 2025 ballot, who garnered at least 5% of the vote and are still eligible for election, as well as 12 players whose last major league appearance was in 2020, played at least 10 seasons in Major League Baseball, and were chosen by a screening committee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] This was the final ballot for Manny Ramirez.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 425 ballots were cast, with 319 votes needed to reach the 75% threshold for election.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] A total of 2,452 votes were cast for individual players, an average of 5.77 votes per ballot.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The Contemporary Baseball Era Committee met in December 2025 at baseball's winter meetings to consider candidates from the era beginning in 1980, players who have been retired at least 15 years and played most of their careers after 1980.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The 16-member committee voted on a ballot listing eight former players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The full ballot was announced on November 3, 2025, and the voting was held on December 7.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The results of the voting were announced on the evening of December 7, with Jeff Kent being elected.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Starting with this ballot, any candidate not receiving at least five votes will be ineligible for consideration in the committee's next ballot, and any candidate who does not receive at least five votes in multiple ballots will be permanently ineligible for all of the committee's future ballots.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] Frick Award is presented annually to a broadcaster for "major contributions to baseball" and has been presented annually since 1978.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The 2026 award will be a composite ballot of local and national voices, as per the rules most recently amended in 2023.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] On December 10, 2025, the Hall of Fame announced Joe Buck as the recipient of the Ford C.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The BBWAA Career Excellence Award honors a baseball writer (or writers) "for meritorious contributions to baseball writing" and is presented during Hall of Fame Weekend by that year's President of the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] The award is voted upon annually by the BBWAA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/2026-baseball-hall-of-fame-balloting] On December 9, 2025, the Hall of Fame announced Paul Hoynes as the recipient of the 2026 BBWAA Career Excellence Award.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] The **All-MLB Team** is an annual Major League Baseball (MLB) honor bestowed upon the best players across both leagues at each position during the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] Selections to the first and second teams are determined by a fan vote and a panel consisting of media members, former players, and baseball officials.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] The career leader in selections is Shohei Ohtani, who has been named an All-MLB player eight times.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] Ohtani is also the only player to be named to both teams in the same season (as a designated hitter and starting pitcher respectively), accomplished in 2021 and 2022, and is the only player to be named to the first team twice in the same season, in 2023.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] The leaders as measured by number of seasons named All-MLB are Yordan Alvarez, Mookie Betts, Freddie Freeman, Aaron Judge, Juan Soto, and Ohtani each of whom has been selected All-MLB in five seasons.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] The roster of each team consists of one catcher, four infielders (one for each position), three outfielders regardless of position, one designated hitter, five starting pitchers, and two relief pitchers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] Before the 2022 season, the designated hitter was only used in the American League (as well as interleague games hosted by American League teams), except during the COVID-19-affected 2020 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/all-mlb-team] The following players have been selected for an All-MLB Team three or more times.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The **Associated Press** (**AP**) is an American not-for-profit news agency headquartered in New York City.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Founded in 1846, it operates as a cooperative, unincorporated association, and produces news reports that are distributed to its members, major U.S. daily newspapers and radio and television broadcasters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Since the Pulitzer Prize was established in 1917, the AP has earned 60 of them, including 36 for photography.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP distributes its widely used *AP Stylebook*, its AP polls tracking NCAA sports, and its election polls and results during U.S. elections.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] It sponsors the National Football League's annual awards.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] By 2016, news collected by the AP was published and republished by more than 1,300 newspapers and broadcasters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP operates 235 news bureaus in 94 countries, and publishes in English, Spanish, and Arabic.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] It also operates the AP Radio Network, which provides twice hourly newscasts and daily sportscasts for broadcast and satellite radio and television stations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Many newspapers and broadcasters outside the United States are AP subscribers, paying a fee to use AP material without being contributing members of the cooperative.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] As part of their cooperative agreement with the AP, most member news organizations grant automatic permission for the AP to distribute their local news reports.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] As of 2025, the AP attracts more than 128 million monthly website visits, making it one of the top 10 news websites in the U.S.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The Associated Press was formed in May 1846 by five daily newspapers in New York City to share the cost of transmitting news of the Mexican–American War.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The venture was organized by Moses Yale Beach (1800–68), second publisher of *The Sun*, joined by the *New York Herald*, the *New York Courier and Enquirer*, *The Journal of Commerce*, and the *New York Evening Express*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Some historians believe that the *New-York Tribune* joined at this time; documents show it was a member in 1849.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] *The New York Times* became a member in September 1851.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Initially known as the New York Associated Press (NYAP), the organization faced competition from the Western Associated Press (1862), which criticized its monopolistic news gathering and price setting practices.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] An investigation completed in 1892 by Victor Lawson, editor and publisher of the *Chicago Daily News*, revealed that several principals of the NYAP entered into a secret agreement with United Press, a rival organization, to share NYAP news and the profits of reselling it.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The findings led to the dissolving of the NYAP.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] That December, the Western Associated Press was incorporated in Illinois as the Associated Press.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] A 1900 Illinois Supreme Court decision (*Inter Ocean Publishing Co. v.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Associated Press*) holding that the AP was a public utility and operating in restraint of trade resulted in the AP's move from Chicago to New York City, where corporation laws were more favorable to cooperatives.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1935, the AP launched the Wirephoto network, which allowed transmission of news photographs over leased private telephone lines on the day they were taken.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] This gave the AP a major advantage over other news media outlets.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] While the first network was only between New York, Chicago, and San Francisco, eventually the AP had its network across the whole United States.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1945, the Supreme Court of the United States held in *Associated Press v.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] United States* that the AP had been violating the Sherman Antitrust Act by prohibiting member newspapers from selling or providing news to nonmember organizations as well as making it very difficult for nonmember newspapers to join the AP.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP entered the broadcast field in 1941 when it began distributing news to radio stations; it created its own radio network in 1974.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1994, it established APTV, a global video newsgathering agency.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] APTV merged with Worldwide Television News in 1998 to form APTN, which provides video to international broadcasters and websites.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2004, the AP moved its headquarters from its long-time home at 50 Rockefeller Plaza to 450 West 33rd Street in Manhattan.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2019, AP had more than 240 bureaus globally.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Its mission has not changed since its founding, but digital technology has made the distribution of the AP news report an interactive endeavor between the AP and its hundreds of U.S. newspaper members, as well as broadcasters, international subscribers, and online customers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP began diversifying its news gathering capabilities.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] By 2007, the AP was generating only about 30% of its revenue from United States newspapers, and by 2024, this had declined to 10%.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] 37% came from the global broadcast customers, 15% from online ventures and 18% came from international newspapers and from photography.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In March 2024, Gannett, the largest U.S. newspaper publisher as measured by total daily circulation, announced that effective March 25, 2024, it would no longer use content from the AP.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] A spokesperson for AP said that they were "shocked and disappointed" by this development.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Newspaper chain McClatchy announced that it would also stop using some AP services.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Gannett and McClatchy will both continue to use AP's election results data.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP's multi-topic structure has resulted in web portals such as Yahoo! and MSN posting its articles, often relying on the AP as their first source for news coverage of breaking news items.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] This and the constant updating evolving stories require has had a major impact on the AP's public image and role, giving new credence to the AP's ongoing mission of having staff for covering every area of news fully and promptly.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2007, Google announced that it was paying to receive AP content, to be displayed in Google News, interrupted from late 2009 to mid-2010 due to a licensing dispute.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] A 2017 study by NewsWhip revealed that AP content was more engaged with on Facebook than content from any individual English-language publisher.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP is governed by an elected board of directors.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Since 2022, the board's chairperson is Gracia C.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Martore, former president and CEO of Tegna, Inc.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] AP reports from countries where press freedom is restricted, sometimes under adverse circumstances, and operates out of more than 100 regional offices.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2025, restrictions preventing AP reporting in the U.S. were imposed by the second Trump administration.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In February 2025, two AP reporters were barred from covering several events at the White House, because of the AP refusal to refer to the Gulf of Mexico as the "Gulf of America", as directed by the White House.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The restrictions against AP were extended to other reporting opportunities such as in Air Force One.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On February 21, 2025, the AP sued the Trump administration in *Associated Press v.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Budowich* for blocking their attendance.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On February 24, 2025, a federal judge declined to issue an immediate order compelling the White House to reinstate access to presidential events to AP, although he encouraged the White House to do so.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On April 8, 2025, Judge Trevor McFadden ruled that the White House must lift the access restrictions they placed on the AP while the *AP v.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On June 6, 2025, the United States Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit imposed a stay upon the lower court's order, allowing the White House to resume barring access to some media events.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP is one of two organizations that collect and verify election results in every city and county across the United States, including races for the U.S. president, the Senate and House of Representatives, and governors as well as other statewide offices.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Known for accuracy, the organization has collected and published presidential election data since 1848.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Major news outlets rely on the polling data and results provided by the Associated Press before declaring a winner in major political races, particularly the presidential election.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In declaring the winners, the AP has historically relied on a robust network of local reporters with first-hand knowledge of assigned territories who also have long-standing relationships with county clerks as well as other local officials.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Moreover, the AP monitors and gathers data from county websites and electronic feeds provided by states.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The research team further verifies the results by considering demographics, number of absentee ballots, and other political issues that may have an effect on the final results.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2018, the AP introduced a new system called AP VoteCast, which was developed together with NORC at the University of Chicago in order to further improve the reliability of its data and overcome biases of its legacy exit poll.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP conducts polls for numerous college sports in the United States.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP college football rankings were created in 1936, and began including the top 25 teams in 1989.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Since 1969, the final poll of each season has been released after all bowl games have been played.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP released its all-time Top 25 in 2016.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] As of 2017, 22 different programs had finished in the number one spot of the poll since its inception.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In the pre-bowl game determination era, the AP poll was often used as the distinction for a national champion in football.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP college basketball poll has been used as a guide for which teams deserve national attention.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP first began its poll of college basketball teams in 1949, and has since conducted over 1,100 polls.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The college basketball poll started with 20 teams and was reduced to 10 during the 1960–61 college basketball season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] It returned to 20 teams in 1968–69 and expanded to 25 beginning in 1989–90.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The final poll for each season is released prior to the conclusion of the NCAA tournament, so all data includes regular season games only.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2017, The AP released a list of the Top 100 teams of all time.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The poll counted poll appearances (one point) and No.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] 1 rankings (two points) to rank each team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP began its Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award in 1959, for a manager in each league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] From 1984 to 2000, the award was given to one manager in all of MLB.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The winners were chosen by a national panel of AP baseball writers and radio men.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Every year, the AP releases the names of the winners of its AP College Basketball Player of the Year and AP College Basketball Coach of the Year awards.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] It also honors a group of All-American players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1994, London-based Associated Press Television (APTV) was founded to provide agency news material to television broadcasters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1998, the AP purchased Worldwide Television News (WTN) from the ABC News division of The Walt Disney Company, Nine Network Australia and ITN London.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP publishes 70,000 videos and 6,000 hours of live video per year, as of 2016.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The agency also provides seven simultaneous live video channels, AP Direct for broadcasters, and six live channels on AP Live Choice for broadcasters and digital publishers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP was the first news agency to launch a live video news service in 2003.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The first publicly available edition of the book was published in 1953.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The first modern edition was published in August 1977 by Lorenz Press.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Afterwards, various paperback editions were published by different publishers, including, among others, Turtleback Books, Penguin's Laurel Press, Pearson's Addison-Wesley, and Hachette's Perseus Books and Basic Books.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Recent editions are released in several formats, including paperback and flat-lying spiral-bound editions, as well as a digital e-book edition and an online subscription version.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Additionally, the *AP Stylebook* also provides English grammar recommendations through social media, including Twitter, Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] From 1977 to 2005, more than two million copies of the *AP Stylebook* were sold worldwide, with that number climbing to 2.5 million by 2011.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Writers in broadcasting, news, magazine publishing, marketing departments, and public relations firms traditionally adopt and apply AP grammar and punctuation styles.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP collaborated with Nazi Germany and gave it access to its photographic archives for its antisemitic Nazi propaganda.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] AP also cooperated with the Nazi regime through censorship.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2017, the German historian Norman Domeier of the University of Vienna brought to wider attention the deal between the AP and the Nazi government related to the interchange of press photos during the period in which the United States was at war with Nazi Germany.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] This relationship involved the Bureau Laux, run by the Waffen-SS photographer Helmut Laux.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The mechanism for this interchange involved a courier flying to Lisbon and back each day transporting photos from and for Nazi Germany's wartime enemy, the United States, via diplomatic pouch.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The transactions were initially conducted at the AP bureau under Luiz Lupi in Lisbon, and from 1944, when the exchange via Lisbon took too long, also at the AP bureau in Stockholm under Eddie Shanke.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Here, as a cover, the Swedish agency, Pressens Bild, was involved as an intermediary.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] An estimated 40,000 photos were exchanged between the enemies in this way.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP was kicked out of Nazi Germany when the United States entered World War II in December 1941.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Israeli journalist Matti Friedman accused the AP of killing a story he wrote about the "war of words", "between Israel and its critics in human rights organizations", in the aftermath of the 2008–2009 Gaza war.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On September 29, 2000, the first day of the Second Intifada, the AP published a photograph of a badly-bloodied young man behind whom a police officer could be seen with a baton raised in a menacing fashion; a gas station with Hebrew lettering could also be seen in the background.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP labelled it with the caption "An Israeli policeman and a Palestinian on the Temple Mount", and the picture and caption were subsequently published in several major American newspapers, including the *New York Times*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In reality, the injured man in the photograph was a Jewish yeshiva student from Chicago named Tuvia Grossman, and the police officer, a Druze named Gidon Tzefadi, was protecting Grossman from a Palestinian mob who had clubbed, stoned, and stabbed Grossman.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] There are also no gas stations with Hebrew lettering on the Temple Mount.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The episode is often cited by those who accuse the media of having an anti-Israel bias, and was the impetus for the founding of the pro-Israel group HonestReporting.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] After a letter from Grossman's father noted the error, the AP, the *New York Times*, and other papers published corrections; despite these corrections, the photograph continues to be used by critics of Israel as a symbol of Israeli aggression and violence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] During the 2021 Israel–Palestine crisis, the Israeli army destroyed the al-Jalaa Highrise, a building housing the AP's Gaza offices and Al Jazeera offices.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Israel stated that the building housed Hamas military intelligence and had given advanced warning of the strike, and no civilians were harmed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] AP CEO Gary Pruitt released a statement on May 16, stating that he "had no indication Hamas was in the building" and called on the Israeli government to provide the evidence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On May 17, US secretary of state Antony Blinken said he had not seen any evidence that Hamas operated from the building housing the AP and Al Jazeera, but it is the job of others to handle intelligence matters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Israel reportedly shared intelligence with American officials and U.S. president Joe Biden showing Hamas offices inside the building.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Reporters Without Borders asked the International Criminal Court to investigate the bombing as a possible war crime.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On June 8, the Israeli ambassador to the US, Gilad Erdan, met with AP CEO Gary Pruitt and vice president for foreign news, Ian Phillips, to discuss the operation.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In coordination with the IDF, Erdan said the site was used by Hamas intelligence officials to develop and carry out electronic warfare operations, and that IDF did not suspect the AP was aware of the alleged covert Hamas presence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] After the meeting the AP stated "We have yet to receive evidence to support these claims".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In May 2024, Israeli officials seized equipment broadcasting a live stream of Northern Gaza from the town of Sderot as part of a ban on Al Jazeera Media in Israel which had received footage from the broadcast.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The move was condemned by multiple journalism organizations, Israeli opposition politicians, and US government officials.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 1994, Tina Susman was on her fourth trip to Somalia, reporting for the AP.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] She was reporting on U.S. peacekeeping troops leaving the country.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Somali rebels outnumbered her bodyguards in Mogadishu, dragged her from her car in broad daylight, and held her for 20 days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] She told *The Quill* that she believes being a woman was an advantage in her experience there.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP had requested news organizations including *The New York Times*, the *Chicago Tribune,* and *The Washington Post* to suppress the story to discourage the emboldening of the kidnappers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In September 2002, Washington, D.C. bureau reporter Christopher Newton, an AP reporter since 1994, was fired after he was accused of fabricating sources since 2000, including at least 40 people and organizations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Prior to his firing, Newton had been focused on writing about federal law enforcement while based at the Justice Department.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Some of the nonexistent agencies quoted in his stories included "Education Alliance", the "Institute for Crime and Punishment in Chicago", "Voice for the Disabled", and "People for Civil Rights".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In 2007, an FBI agent working in Seattle impersonated an AP journalist and infected the computer of a 15-year-old suspect with malicious surveillance software.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The incident sparked a strongly worded statement from the AP demanding that the bureau never impersonate a member of the news media again.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In September 2016, the incident resulted in a report by the Justice Department, which the AP said "effectively condone[d] the FBI's impersonation".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In December 2017, following a US court appearance, a judge ruled in favor of the AP in a lawsuit against the FBI for fraudulently impersonating a member of the news media in conjunction with the 2007 case.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In June 2008, the AP sent numerous DMCA take-down demands and threatened legal action against several blogs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP contended that the internet blogs were violating the AP's copyright by linking to AP material and using headlines and short summaries in those links.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Many bloggers and experts noted that the use of the AP news fell squarely under commonly accepted internet practices and within fair-use standards.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Others noted and demonstrated that the AP routinely takes similar excerpts from other sources, often without attribution or licenses.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP responded that it was defining standards regarding citations of AP news.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In March 2009, the AP counter-sued artist Shepard Fairey over his famous image of Barack Obama, saying the uncredited, uncompensated use of an AP photo violated copyright laws and signaled a threat to journalism.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Fairey had sued the AP the previous month over his artwork, titled "Obama Hope" and "Obama Progress", arguing that he did not violate copyright law because he dramatically changed the image.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The artwork, based on an April 2006 picture taken for the AP by Mannie Garcia, was a popular image during the 2008 presidential election and now hangs in the National Portrait Gallery in Washington, D.C.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] According to the AP's lawsuit filed in federal court in Manhattan, Fairey knowingly "misappropriated The AP's rights in that image".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The suit asked the court to award the AP profits made off the image and damages.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Fairey said he looked forward to "upholding the free expression rights at stake here" and disproving the AP's accusations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In January 2011, the suit was settled with neither side declaring their position to be wrong but agreeing to share reproduction rights and profits from Fairey's work.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In January 2008, the AP sued competitor All Headline News (AHN) claiming that AHN allegedly infringed on its copyrights and a contentious "quasi-property" right to facts.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP complaint asserted that AHN reporters had copied facts from AP news reports without permission and without paying a syndication fee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] After AHN moved to dismiss all but the copyright claims set forth by the AP, a majority of the lawsuit was dismissed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The case has been dismissed and both parties settled.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On April 23, 2013, hackers posted a tweet to AP's Twitter account about fictional attacks on the White House, falsely claiming that President Obama had been injured.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The hoax caused a flash crash on the American stock markets, with the Dow Jones Industrial Average briefly falling by 143 points.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On May 13, 2013, the AP announced that telephone records for 20 of their reporters during a two-month period in 2012 had been subpoenaed by the U.S.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Justice Department and described these acts as a "massive and unprecedented intrusion" into news-gathering operations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The DOJ did not direct subpoenas to the AP, instead going to their phone providers, including Verizon Wireless.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Attorney General Eric Holder testified under oath in front of the House Judiciary Committee that he recused himself from the leak investigations to avoid any appearance of a conflict of interest.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Holder said his Deputy Attorney General, James M.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Cole, was in charge of the AP investigation and would have ordered the subpoenas.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] On January 10, 2022, AP announced it would start selling non-fungible tokens (NFTs) of their photographs in partnership with a company named Xooa, with the proceeds being used to fund their operations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] One of the NFTs they promoted on Twitter on 24 February was an aerial shot depicting an overcrowded migrant boat in the Mediterranean Sea by Brazilian photojournalist Felipe Dana.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The sale received negative backlash from users and other journalists, with AP being accused of profiting off of human suffering and the picture choice being "dystopian" and "in extremely poor taste".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The tweet was subsequently deleted and the NFT, which was to be sold the next day, was pulled from market.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] Global director of media relations Lauren Easton apologized, saying "This was a poor choice of imagery for an NFT.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] It has not and will not be put up for auction ...
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] AP's NFT marketplace is a very early pilot program, and we are immediately reviewing our efforts".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP has earned 59 Pulitzer Prizes, including 36 for photography, since the award was established in 1917.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] In May 2020, Dar Yasin, Mukhtar Khan, and Channi Anand of the AP were honored with the 2020 Pulitzer Prize for Feature Photography.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The choice caused controversy, because it was taken by some as questioning "India's legitimacy over Kashmir" as it had used the word "independence" in regard to revocation of Article 370.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/associated-press] The AP won an Oscar in 2024 for the documentary film *20 Days in Mariupol*, a first-person account of the early days of Russia's invasion of Ukraine in 2022.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] In 1914, Ruth was signed to play Minor League baseball for the Baltimore Orioles but was soon sold to the Red Sox.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] By 1916, he had built a reputation as an outstanding pitcher who sometimes hit long home runs, a feat unusual for any player in the dead-ball era.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Although Ruth twice won 23 games in a season as a pitcher and was a member of three World Series championship teams with the Red Sox, he wanted to play every day and was allowed to convert to an outfielder.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] With regular playing time, he broke the MLB single-season home run record in 1919 with 29.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] After that season, Red Sox owner Harry Frazee sold Ruth to the Yankees amid controversy.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] The trade fueled Boston's subsequent 86-year championship drought and popularized the "Curse of the Bambino" superstition.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] In his 15 years with the Yankees, Ruth helped the team win seven American League (AL) pennants and four World Series championships.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] His big swing led to escalating home run totals that not only drew fans to the ballpark and boosted the sport's popularity but also helped usher in baseball's live-ball era, which evolved from a low-scoring game of strategy to a sport where the home run was a major factor.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] As part of the Yankees' vaunted "Murderers' Row" lineup of 1927, Ruth hit 60 home runs, which extended his own MLB single-season record by a single home run.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's last season with the Yankees was 1934, and he retired after a short stint with the Boston Braves the following year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] In his career, he led the AL in home runs 12 times.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] During Ruth's career, he was the target of intense press and public attention for his baseball exploits and off-field penchants for drinking and womanizing.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] After his retirement as a player, he was denied the opportunity to manage a major league club, most likely because of poor behavior during parts of his playing career.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] In his final years, Ruth made many public appearances, especially in support of American efforts in World War II.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] In 1946, he became ill with nasopharyngeal cancer and died from the disease two years later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth remains a major figure in American culture.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] George Herman Ruth Jr. was born on February 6, 1895, at 216 Emory Street in the Pigtown neighborhood of Baltimore, in a house which belonged to his maternal grandfather Pius Schamberger, a German immigrant and trade unionist.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's parents, Katherine (née Schamberger) and George Herman Ruth Sr., were both of German ancestry.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth Sr. worked a series of jobs that included lightning rod salesman and streetcar operator.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] The elder Ruth then became a counterman in a family-owned combination grocery and saloon business.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Only one of Ruth's seven siblings, his younger sister Mamie, survived infancy.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Many details of Ruth's childhood are unknown.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] When Ruth was a toddler, the family moved to 339 South Woodyear Street; by the time he was six years old, his father had a saloon with an upstairs apartment at 426 West Camden Street.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Details are equally scanty about why Ruth was sent at the age of seven to St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's Industrial School for Boys, a reformatory and orphanage.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] However, according to Julia Ruth Stevens' recount in 1999, because George Sr. was a saloon owner and had given Ruth little supervision, he became a delinquent.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] As an adult, Ruth admitted that as a youth he ran the streets, rarely attended school, and drank beer when his father was not looking.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Some accounts say that following a violent incident at his father's saloon, the city authorities decided that this environment was unsuitable for a child.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He was recorded as "incorrigible" and spent much of the next 12 years there.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's boys received an education, students were also expected to learn work skills and help operate the school, particularly once the boys turned 12.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth became a shirtmaker and was also a proficient carpenter.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He would adjust his own shirt collars, even during his well-paid baseball career.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] The boys, aged 5 to 21, did most of the work around the facility, and renovated St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] The food was simple, and the Xaverian Brothers who ran the school insisted on strict discipline; corporal punishment was common.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth's nickname there was "Niggerlips", as he had large facial features and was darker than most boys at the all-white reformatory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth was sometimes allowed to rejoin his family or was placed at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] James's Home, a supervised residence with work in the community, but he was always returned to St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He was rarely visited by his family; his mother died when he was 12 and, by some accounts, he was permitted to leave St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] How Ruth came to play baseball there is uncertain: according to one account, his placement at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's was due in part to repeatedly breaking windows with long hits while playing street ball; by another, he was told to join a team on his first day at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's by the school's athletic director, Brother Herman, becoming a catcher even though left-handers rarely play that position.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] During his time there he also played third base and shortstop, again unusual for a left-hander, and was forced to wear gloves made for right-handers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He was encouraged in his pursuits by the school's Prefect of Discipline, Brother Matthias Boutlier.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Brother Matthias was greatly respected by the boys both for his strength and for his fairness.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] For the rest of his life, Ruth would praise Brother Matthias, and his running and hitting styles closely resembled his teacher's.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth stated, "I think I was born as a hitter the first day I ever saw him hit a baseball." The older man became a mentor and role model to Ruth; biographer Robert W.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth (top row, left, holding a catcher's mitt and mask) at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] The school's influence remained with Ruth in other ways.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He was a lifelong Catholic who would sometimes attend Mass after carousing all night, and he became a well-known member of the Knights of Columbus.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He would visit orphanages, schools, and hospitals throughout his life, often avoiding publicity.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's as he became famous and rich, donating money and his presence at fundraisers, and spending $5,000 to buy Brother Matthias a Cadillac in 1926—subsequently replacing it when it was destroyed in an accident.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Nevertheless, his biographer Leigh Montville suggests that many of the off-the-field excesses of Ruth's career were driven by the deprivations of his time at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's played baseball in organized leagues at different levels of proficiency.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Ruth later estimated that he played 200 games a year as he steadily climbed the ladder of success.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Although he played all positions at one time or another, he gained stardom as a pitcher.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] According to Brother Matthias, Ruth was laughing at the bumbling pitching efforts of fellow students, and Matthias told him to go in and see if he could do better.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] Mary's, and when he was 18 in 1913, he was allowed to leave the premises to play weekend games on community teams.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p01] He was mentioned in several newspaper articles, for both his pitching prowess and ability to hit long home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In early 1914, Ruth signed a professional baseball contract with Jack Dunn, who owned and managed the minor-league Baltimore Orioles, an International League team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The circumstances of Ruth's signing are not known with certainty.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] By some accounts, Dunn was urged to attend a game between an all-star team from St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's and one from another Xaverian facility, Mount St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Some versions have Ruth running away before the eagerly awaited game, to be punished, and then returning to pitch St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Others have Washington Senators pitcher Joe Engel, a Mount St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's graduate, pitching in an alumni game after watching a preliminary contest between the college's freshmen and a team from St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Engel watched Ruth play, then told Dunn about him at a chance meeting in Washington.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, in his autobiography, stated only that he worked out for Dunn for a half hour, and was signed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] According to biographer Kal Wagenheim, there were legal difficulties to be straightened out as Ruth was supposed to remain at the school until he turned 21, though SportsCentury stated in a documentary that Ruth had already been discharged from St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's when he turned 19, and earned a monthly salary of $100.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The train journey to spring training in Fayetteville, North Carolina, in March was likely Ruth's first outside the Baltimore area.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The rookie ballplayer was the subject of various pranks by veteran players, who were probably also the source of his famous nickname.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] There are various accounts of how Ruth came to be called "Babe", but most center on his being referred to as "Dunnie's babe" (or some variant).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] SportsCentury reported that his nickname was gained because he was the new "darling" or "project" of Dunn, not only because of Ruth's raw talent, but also because of his lack of knowledge of the proper etiquette of eating out in a restaurant, being in a hotel, or being on a train.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] "Babe" was, at that time, a common nickname in baseball, with perhaps the most famous to that point being Pittsburgh Pirates pitcher and 1909 World Series hero Babe Adams, who appeared younger than his actual age.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth made his first appearance as a professional ballplayer in an inter-squad game on March 7, 1914.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He played shortstop and pitched the last two innings of a 15–9 victory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In his second at-bat, Ruth hit a long home run to right field; the blast was locally reported to be longer than a legendary shot hit by Jim Thorpe in Fayetteville.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth made his first appearance against a team in organized baseball in an exhibition game versus the major-league Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched the middle three innings and gave up two runs in the fourth, but then settled down and pitched a scoreless fifth and sixth innings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In a game against the Phillies the following afternoon, Ruth entered during the sixth inning and did not allow a run the rest of the way.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Orioles scored seven runs in the bottom of the eighth inning to overcome a 6–0 deficit, and Ruth was the winning pitcher.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Once the regular season began, Ruth was a star pitcher who was also dangerous at the plate.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The team performed well, yet received almost no attention from the Baltimore press.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] A third major league, the Federal League, had begun play, and the local franchise, the Baltimore Terrapins, restored that city to the major leagues for the first time since 1902.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Few fans visited Oriole Park, where Ruth and his teammates labored in relative obscurity.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth may have been offered a bonus and a larger salary to jump to the Terrapins; when rumors to that effect swept Baltimore, giving Ruth the most publicity he had experienced to date, a Terrapins official denied it, stating it was their policy not to sign players under contract to Dunn.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The competition from the Terrapins caused Dunn to sustain large losses.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Although by late June the Orioles were in first place, having won over two-thirds of their games, the paid attendance dropped as low as 150.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Dunn explored a possible move by the Orioles to Richmond, Virginia, as well as the sale of a minority interest in the club.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] These possibilities fell through, leaving Dunn with little choice other than to sell his best players to major league teams to raise money.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He offered Ruth to the reigning World Series champions, Connie Mack's Philadelphia Athletics, but Mack had his own financial problems.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Cincinnati Reds and New York Giants expressed interest in Ruth, but Dunn sold his contract, along with those of pitchers Ernie Shore and Ben Egan, to the Boston Red Sox of the American League (AL) on July 4.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The sale price was announced as $25,000 but other reports lower the amount to half that, or possibly $8,500 plus the cancellation of a $3,000 loan.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth remained with the Orioles for several days while the Red Sox completed a road trip, and reported to the team in Boston on July 11.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On July 11, 1914, Ruth arrived in Boston with Egan and Shore.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth later told the story of how that morning he had met Helen Woodford, who would become his first wife.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] She was a 16-year-old waitress at Landers Coffee Shop, and Ruth related that she served him when he had breakfast there.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Other stories, though, suggested that the meeting occurred on another day, and perhaps under other circumstances.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Regardless of when he began to court his first wife, he won his first game as a pitcher for the Red Sox that afternoon, 4–3, over the Cleveland Naps.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] His catcher was Bill Carrigan, who was also the Red Sox manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Shore was given a start by Carrigan the next day; he won that and his second start and thereafter was pitched regularly.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth lost his second start, and was thereafter little used.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In his major league debut as a batter, Ruth went 0-for-2 against left-hander Willie Mitchell, striking out in his first at bat before being removed for a pinch hitter in the seventh inning.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was not much noticed by the fans, as Bostonians watched the Red Sox's crosstown rivals, the Braves, begin a legendary comeback that would take them from last place on the Fourth of July to the 1914 World Series championship.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Egan was traded to Cleveland after two weeks on the Boston roster.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] During his time with the Red Sox, he kept an eye on the inexperienced Ruth, much as Dunn had in Baltimore.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] When he was traded, no one took his place as supervisor.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's new teammates considered him brash and would have preferred him as a rookie to remain quiet and inconspicuous.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] When Ruth insisted on taking batting practice despite being both a rookie who did not play regularly and a pitcher, he arrived to find his bats sawed in half.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] His teammates nicknamed him "the Big Baboon", a name the swarthy Ruth, who had disliked the nickname "Niggerlips" at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had received a raise on promotion to the major leagues and quickly acquired tastes for fine food, liquor, and women, among other temptations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Manager Carrigan allowed Ruth to pitch two exhibition games in mid-August.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Although Ruth won both against minor-league competition, he was not restored to the pitching rotation.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] It is uncertain why Carrigan did not give Ruth additional opportunities to pitch.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] There are legends—incorporated into the 1948 film *The Babe Ruth Story*—that Ruth had a habit of signaling his intent to throw a curveball by sticking out his tongue slightly, and that he was easy to hit until this changed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Creamer pointed out that it is common for inexperienced pitchers to display such habits, and needing to break this habit would not constitute a reason to not use him at all; Creamer suggested Carrigan was unwilling to use Ruth due to the rookie's poor behavior.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On July 30, 1914, Boston owner Joseph Lannin had purchased the minor-league Providence Grays, members of the International League.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Providence team had been owned by several people associated with the Detroit Tigers, including star hitter Ty Cobb, and as part of the transaction, a Providence pitcher was sent to the Tigers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] To soothe Providence fans upset at losing a star, Lannin announced that the Red Sox would soon send a replacement to the Grays.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] This was intended to be Ruth, but his departure for Providence was delayed when Cincinnati Reds owner Garry Herrmann claimed him by waiver.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] After Lannin wrote to Herrmann explaining that the Red Sox wanted Ruth in Providence so he could develop as a player, and would not release him to a major league club, Herrmann allowed Ruth to be sent to the minors.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan later stated that Ruth was not sent down to Providence to make him a better player, but to help the Grays win the International League pennant (league championship).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth joined the Grays on August 18, 1914.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] After Dunn's deals, the Baltimore Orioles managed to hold on to first place until August 15, after which they continued to fade, leaving the pennant race between Providence and Rochester.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was deeply impressed by Providence manager "Wild Bill" Donovan, previously a star pitcher with a 25–4 win–loss record for Detroit in 1907; in later years, he credited Donovan with teaching him much about pitching.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was often called upon to pitch, in one stretch starting (and winning) four games in eight days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On September 5 at Maple Leaf Park in Toronto, Ruth pitched a one-hit 9–0 victory, and hit his first professional home run, his only one as a minor leaguer, off Ellis Johnson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Recalled to Boston after Providence finished the season in first place, he pitched and won a game for the Red Sox against the New York Yankees on October 2, getting his first major league hit, a double.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth finished the season with a record of 2–1 as a major leaguer and 23–8 in the International League (for Baltimore and Providence).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Once the season concluded, Ruth married Helen in Ellicott City, Maryland.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Creamer speculated that they did not marry in Baltimore, where the newlyweds boarded with George Ruth Sr., to avoid possible interference from those at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Mary's—both bride and groom were not yet of age and Ruth remained on parole from that institution until his 21st birthday.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In March 1915, Ruth reported to Hot Springs, Arkansas, for his first major league spring training.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was ineffective in his first start, taking the loss in the third game of the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Injuries and ineffective pitching by other Boston pitchers gave Ruth another chance, and after some good relief appearances, Carrigan allowed Ruth another start, and he won a rain-shortened seven inning game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ten days later, the manager had him start against the New York Yankees at the Polo Grounds.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth took a 3–2 lead into the ninth, but lost the game 4–3 in 13 innings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, hitting ninth as was customary for pitchers, hit a massive home run into the upper deck in right field off of Jack Warhop.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] At the time, home runs were rare in baseball, and Ruth's majestic shot awed the crowd.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The winning pitcher, Warhop, would in August 1915 conclude a major league career of eight seasons, undistinguished but for being the first major league pitcher to give up a home run to Babe Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan was sufficiently impressed by Ruth's pitching to give him a spot in the starting rotation.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth finished the 1915 season 18–8 as a pitcher; as a hitter, he batted .315 and had four home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox won the AL pennant, but with the pitching staff healthy, Ruth was not called upon to pitch in the 1915 World Series against the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was used as a pinch hitter in Game Five, but grounded out against Phillies ace Grover Cleveland Alexander.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Despite his success as a pitcher, Ruth was acquiring a reputation for long home runs; at Sportsman's Park against the St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Louis Browns, a Ruth hit soared over Grand Avenue, breaking the window of a Chevrolet dealership.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1916, attention focused on Ruth's pitching as he engaged in repeated pitching duels with Washington Senators' ace Walter Johnson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The two met five times during the season with Ruth winning four and Johnson one (Ruth had a no decision in Johnson's victory).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Two of Ruth's victories were by the score of 1–0, one in a 13-inning game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Of the 1–0 shutout decided without extra innings, AL president Ban Johnson stated, "That was one of the best ball games I have ever seen." For the season, Ruth went 23–12, with a 1.75 ERA and nine shutouts, both of which led the league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's nine shutouts in 1916 set a league record for left-handers that would remain unmatched until Ron Guidry tied it in 1978.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox won the pennant and World Series again, this time defeating the Brooklyn Robins (as the Dodgers were then known) in five games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth started and won Game 2, 2–1, in 14 innings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Until another game of that length was played in 2005, this was the longest World Series game, and Ruth's pitching performance is still the longest postseason complete game victory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Carrigan retired as player and manager after 1916, returning to his native Maine to be a businessman.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, who played under four managers who are in the National Baseball Hall of Fame, always maintained that Carrigan, who is not enshrined there, was the best skipper he ever played for.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] There were other changes in the Red Sox organization that offseason, as Lannin sold the team to a three-man group headed by New York theatrical promoter Harry Frazee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Jack Barry was hired by Frazee as manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched a league-leading 35 complete games and went 24–13 with a 2.01 ERA and six shutouts in 1917, but the Sox finished in second place in the league, nine games behind the Chicago White Sox in the standings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On June 23 at Washington, when home plate umpire 'Brick' Owens called the first four pitches as balls, Ruth was ejected from the game and threw a punch at him, for which Ruth was suspended for ten days and fined $100.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ernie Shore was called in to relieve Ruth, and was allowed eight warm-up pitches.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The runner who had reached base on the walk was caught stealing, and Shore retired all 26 batters he faced to win the game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Until 1991, this was listed as a perfect game for Ernie Shore.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1991, Major League Baseball's (MLB) Committee on Statistical Accuracy amended it to be listed as a combined no-hitter.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1917, Ruth was used little as a batter, other than for his plate appearances while pitching, and hit .325 with two home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The United States' entry into World War I occurred at the start of the season and overshadowed baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Conscription was introduced in September 1917, and most baseball players in the big leagues were of draft age.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] This included Barry, who was a player-manager, and who joined the Naval Reserve in an attempt to avoid the draft, only to be called up after the 1917 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Frazee hired International League President Ed Barrow as Red Sox manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow had spent the previous 30 years in a variety of baseball jobs, though he never played the game professionally.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] With the major leagues shorthanded because of the war, Barrow had many holes in the Red Sox lineup to fill.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth also noticed these vacancies in the lineup.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He was dissatisfied in the role of a pitcher who appeared every four or five days and wanted to play every day at another position.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used Ruth at first base and in the outfield during the exhibition season, but he restricted him to pitching as the team moved toward Boston and the season opener.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] At the time, Ruth was possibly the best left-handed pitcher in baseball, and allowing him to play another position was an experiment that could have backfired.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Inexperienced as a manager, Barrow had player Harry Hooper advise him on baseball game strategy.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Hooper urged his manager to allow Ruth to play another position when he was not pitching, arguing to Barrow, who had invested in the club, that the crowds were larger on days when Ruth played, as they were attracted by his hitting.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In early May, Barrow gave in; Ruth promptly hit home runs in four consecutive games (one an exhibition), the last off of Walter Johnson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] For the first time in his career (disregarding pinch-hitting appearances), Ruth was assigned a place in the batting order higher than ninth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Although Barrow predicted that Ruth would beg to return to pitching the first time he experienced a batting slump, that did not occur.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used Ruth primarily as an outfielder in the war-shortened 1918 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth hit .300, with 11 home runs, enough to secure him a share of the major league home run title with Tilly Walker of the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He was still occasionally used as a pitcher, and had a 13–7 record with a 2.22 ERA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On July 8, in the bottom of the ninth inning in a scoreless game, with a runner on first base Ruth hit a ball out of the ballpark to drive in the game-winning run; this was recorded as a triple, since the rules at that time considered the game over once the winning run scored.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1968 the Special Baseball Records Committee unanimously ruled this, along with 36 other hits, a home run, but in part due to the perceived importance of preserving Ruth's home run total at 714, in 1969 the committee reversed this decision.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1918, the Red Sox won their third pennant in four years and faced the Chicago Cubs in the World Series, which began on September 5, the earliest date in history.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The season had been shortened because the government had ruled that baseball players who were eligible for the military would have to be inducted or work in critical war industries, such as armaments plants.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth pitched and won Game One for the Red Sox, a 1–0 shutout.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Before Game Four, Ruth injured his left hand in a fight but pitched anyway.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He gave up seven hits and six walks, but was helped by outstanding fielding behind him and by his own batting efforts, as a fourth-inning triple by Ruth gave his team a 2–0 lead.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Cubs tied the game in the eighth inning, but the Red Sox scored to take a 3–2 lead again in the bottom of that inning.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] After Ruth gave up a hit and a walk to start the ninth inning, he was relieved on the mound by Joe Bush.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] To keep Ruth and his bat in the game, he was sent to play left field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Bush retired the side to give Ruth his second win of the Series, and the third and last World Series pitching victory of his career, against no defeats, in three pitching appearances.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's effort gave his team a three-games-to-one lead, and two days later the Red Sox won their third Series in four years, four-games-to-two.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Before allowing the Cubs to score in Game Four, Ruth pitched 29+2⁄3 consecutive scoreless innings, a World Series record that stood for more than 40 years until 1961, broken by Whitey Ford.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth was prouder of that record than he was of any of his batting feats.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] With the World Series over, Ruth gained exemption from the war draft by accepting a nominal position with a Pennsylvania steel mill.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Many industrial establishments took pride in their baseball teams and sought to hire major leaguers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The end of the war in November set Ruth free to play baseball without such contrivances.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] During the 1919 season, Ruth was used as a pitcher in only 17 of his 130 games and compiled a 9–5 record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Barrow used him as a pitcher mostly in the early part of the season, when the Red Sox still had hopes of a second consecutive pennant.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] By late June, the Red Sox were clearly out of the race, and Barrow had no objection to Ruth concentrating on his hitting, if only because it drew people to the ballpark.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had hit a home run against the Yankees on Opening Day, and another during a month-long batting slump that soon followed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Relieved of his pitching duties, Ruth began an unprecedented spell of slugging home runs, which gave him widespread public and press attention.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Two home runs by Ruth on July 5, and one in each of two consecutive games a week later, raised his season total to 11, tying his career best from 1918.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The first record to fall was the AL single-season mark of 16, set by Ralph "Socks" Seybold in 1902.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth matched that on July 29, then pulled ahead toward the major league record of 25, set by Buck Freeman in 1899.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] By the time Ruth reached this in early September, writers had discovered that Ned Williamson of the 1884 Chicago White Stockings had hit 27—though in a ballpark where the distance to right field was only 215 feet (66 m).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On September 20, "Babe Ruth Day" at Fenway Park, Ruth won the game with a home run in the bottom of the ninth inning, tying Williamson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He broke the record four days later against the Yankees at the Polo Grounds, and hit one more against the Senators to finish with 29.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The home run at Washington made Ruth the first major league player to hit a home run at all eight ballparks in his league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In spite of Ruth's hitting heroics, the Red Sox finished sixth, 20+1⁄2 games behind the league champion White Sox.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In his six seasons with Boston, he won 89 games and recorded a 2.19 ERA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He had a four-year stretch where he was second in the AL in wins and ERA behind Walter Johnson, and Ruth had a winning record against Johnson in head-to-head matchups.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] As an out-of-towner from New York City, Frazee had been regarded with suspicion by Boston's sportswriters and baseball fans when he bought the team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He won them over with success on the field and a willingness to build the Red Sox by purchasing or trading for players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He offered the Senators $60,000 for Walter Johnson, but Washington owner Clark Griffith was unwilling.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Even so, Frazee was successful in bringing other players to Boston, especially as replacements for players in the military.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] This willingness to spend for players helped the Red Sox secure the 1918 title.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The 1919 season saw record-breaking attendance, and Ruth's home runs for Boston made him a national sensation.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In March 1919 Ruth was reported as having accepted a three-year contract for a total of $27,000, after protracted negotiations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, on December 26, 1919, Frazee sold Ruth's contract to the New York Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Not all the circumstances concerning the sale are known, but brewer and former congressman Jacob Ruppert, the New York team's principal owner, reportedly asked Yankee manager Miller Huggins what the team needed to be successful.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] "Get Ruth from Boston", Huggins supposedly replied, noting that Frazee was perennially in need of money to finance his theatrical productions.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] An often-told story is that Frazee needed money, and sold Ruth to finance the musical *No, No, Nanette*; that play did not open until 1925, by which time Frazee had sold the Red Sox, but was based on a Frazee-produced play, *My Lady Friends*, which opened in 1919.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] There were also other financial pressures on Frazee, despite his team's success.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth, fully aware of baseball's popularity and his role in it, wanted to renegotiate his contract, signed before the 1919 season for $10,000 per year through 1921.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] He demanded that his salary be doubled, or he would sit out the season and cash in on his popularity through other ventures.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth's salary demands were causing other players to ask for more money.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Additionally, Frazee still owed Lannin as much as $125,000 from the purchase of the club.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, when Frazee, who moved in the same social circles as Huston, hinted to the colonel that Ruth was available for the right price, the Yankees owners quickly pursued the purchase.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Frazee sold the rights to Babe Ruth for $100,000, the largest sum ever paid for a baseball player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The deal also involved a $350,000 loan from Ruppert to Frazee, secured by a mortgage on Fenway Park.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Once it was agreed, Frazee informed Barrow, who, stunned, told the owner that he was getting the worse end of the bargain.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Cynics have suggested that Barrow may have played a larger role in the Ruth sale, as less than a year after, he became the Yankee general manager, and in the following years made a number of purchases of Red Sox players from Frazee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The $100,000 price included $25,000 in cash, and notes for the same amount due November 1 in 1920, 1921, and 1922; Ruppert and Huston assisted Frazee in selling the notes to banks for immediate cash.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The transaction was contingent on Ruth signing a new contract, which was quickly accomplished—Ruth agreed to fulfill the remaining two years on his contract, but was given a $20,000 bonus, payable over two seasons.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The deal was announced on January 6, 1920.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Reaction in Boston was mixed: some fans were embittered at the loss of Ruth; others conceded that Ruth had become difficult to deal with.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] According to Marty Appel in his history of the Yankees, the transaction, "changed the fortunes of two high-profile franchises for decades".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Red Sox, winners of five of the first 16 World Series, those played between 1903 and 1919, would not win another pennant until 1946, or another World Series until 2004, a drought attributed in baseball superstition to Frazee's sale of Ruth and sometimes dubbed the "Curse of the Bambino".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Conversely, the Yankees had not won the AL championship prior to their acquisition of Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] They won seven AL pennants and four World Series with him, and lead baseball with 41 pennants and 27 World Series titles in their history.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] When Ruth signed with the Yankees, his transition from a pitcher to a power-hitting outfielder was complete.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] His 15-season Yankee career consisted of over 2,000 games, and Ruth broke many batting records while making only five widely scattered appearances on the mound, winning all of them.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] At the end of April 1920, the Yankees were 4–7, with the Red Sox leading the league with a 10–2 mark.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth had done little, having injured himself swinging the bat.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Both situations began to change on May 1, when Ruth hit a tape measure home run that sent the ball completely out of the Polo Grounds, a feat believed to have been previously accomplished only by Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees won, 6–0, taking three out of four from the Red Sox.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth hit his second home run on May 2, and by the end of the month had set a major league record for home runs in a month with 11, and promptly broke it with 13 in June.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Fans responded with record attendance figures.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] On May 16, Ruth and the Yankees drew 38,600 to the Polo Grounds, a record for the ballpark, and 15,000 fans were turned away.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Large crowds jammed stadiums to see Ruth play when the Yankees were on the road.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruth tied his own record of 29 on July 15 and broke it with home runs in both games of a doubleheader four days later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] By the end of July, he had 37, but his pace slackened somewhat after that.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Nevertheless, on September 4, he both tied and broke the organized baseball record for home runs in a season, snapping Perry Werden's 1895 mark of 44 in the minor Western League.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees played well as a team, battling for the league lead early in the summer, but slumped in August in the AL pennant battle with Chicago and Cleveland.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The pennant and the World Series were won by Cleveland, who surged ahead after the Black Sox Scandal broke on September 28 and led to the suspension of many of Chicago's top players, including Shoeless Joe Jackson.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The Yankees finished third, but drew 1.2 million fans to the Polo Grounds, the first time a team had drawn a seven-figure attendance.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The rest of the league sold 600,000 more tickets, many fans there to see Ruth, who led the league with 54 home runs, 158 runs, and 137 runs batted in (RBIs).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In 1920 and afterwards, Ruth was aided in his power hitting by the fact that A.J.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Reach Company—the maker of baseballs used in the major leagues—was using a more efficient machine to wind the yarn found within the baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The new baseballs went into play in 1920 and ushered the start of the live-ball era; the number of home runs across the major leagues increased by 184 over the previous year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Yankees business manager Harry Sparrow had died early in the 1920 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] Ruppert and Huston hired Barrow to replace him.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] The two men quickly made a deal with Frazee for New York to acquire some of the players who would be mainstays of the early Yankee pennant-winning teams, including catcher Wally Schang and pitcher Waite Hoyt.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p02] In the offseason, Ruth spent some time in Havana, Cuba, where he was said to have lost $35,000 (equivalent to $630,000 in 2025) betting on horse races.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit home runs early and often in the 1921 season, during which he broke Roger Connor's mark for home runs in a career, 138.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Each of the almost 600 home runs Ruth hit in his career after that extended his own record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After a slow start, the Yankees were soon locked in a tight pennant race with Cleveland, winners of the 1920 World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On September 15, Ruth hit his 55th home run, breaking his year-old single-season record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In late September, the Yankees visited Cleveland and won three out of four games, giving them the upper hand in the race, and clinched their first pennant a few days later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth finished the regular season with 59 home runs, batting .378 and with a slugging percentage of .846.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's 177 runs scored, 119 extra-base hits, and 457 total bases set modern-era records that still stand as of 2024.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees had high expectations when they met the New York Giants in the 1921 World Series, every game of which was played in the Polo Grounds.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees won the first two games with Ruth in the lineup.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, Ruth badly scraped his elbow during Game 2 when he slid into third base (he had walked and stolen both second and third bases).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After the game, he was told by the team physician not to play the rest of the series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Despite this advice, he did play in the next three games, and pinch-hit in Game Eight of the best-of-nine series, but the Yankees lost, five games to three.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .316, drove in five runs and hit his first World Series home run.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After the Series, Ruth and teammates Bob Meusel and Bill Piercy participated in a barnstorming tour in the Northeast.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] A rule then in force prohibited World Series participants from playing in exhibition games during the offseason, the purpose being to prevent Series participants from replicating the Series and undermining its value.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Baseball Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis suspended the trio until May 20, 1922, and fined them their 1921 World Series checks.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In August 1922, the rule was changed to allow limited barnstorming for World Series participants, with Landis's permission required.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On March 4, 1922, Ruth signed a new contract for three years at $52,000 a year (equivalent to $1,000,000 in 2025).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] This was more than two times the largest sum ever paid to a ballplayer up to that point and it represented 40% of the team's player payroll.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Despite his suspension, Ruth was named the Yankees' new on-field captain prior to the 1922 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During the suspension, he worked out with the team in the morning and played exhibition games with the Yankees on their off days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He and Meusel returned on May 20 to a sellout crowd at the Polo Grounds, but Ruth batted 0-for-4 and was booed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On May 25, he was thrown out of the game for throwing dust in umpire George Hildebrand's face, then climbed into the stands to confront a heckler.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ban Johnson ordered him fined, suspended, and stripped of position as team captain.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In his shortened season, Ruth appeared in 110 games, batted .315, with 35 home runs, and drove in 99 runs, but the 1922 season was a disappointment in comparison to his two previous dominating years.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Despite Ruth's off-year, the Yankees managed to win the pennant and faced the New York Giants in the World Series for the second consecutive year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the Series, Giants manager John McGraw instructed his pitchers to throw him nothing but curveballs, and Ruth never adjusted.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had just two hits in 17 at bats, and the Yankees lost to the Giants for the second straight year, by 4–0 (with one tie game).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Sportswriter Joe Vila called him, "an exploded phenomenon".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After the season, Ruth was a guest at an Elks Club banquet, set up by Ruth's agent with Yankee team support.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] There, each speaker, concluding with future New York mayor Jimmy Walker, censured him for his poor behavior.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] An emotional Ruth promised reform, and, to the surprise of many, followed through.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When he reported to spring training, he was in his best shape as a Yankee, weighing only 210 pounds (95 kg).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees' status as tenants of the Giants at the Polo Grounds had become increasingly uneasy, and in 1922, Giants owner Charles Stoneham said the Yankees' lease, expiring after that season, would not be renewed.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert and Huston had long contemplated a new stadium, and had taken an option on property at 161st Street and River Avenue in the Bronx.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Yankee Stadium was completed in time for the home opener on April 18, 1923, at which Ruth hit the first home run in what was quickly dubbed "the House that Ruth Built".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The ballpark was designed with Ruth in mind: although the venue's left-field fence was further from home plate than at the Polo Grounds, Yankee Stadium's right-field fence was closer, making home runs easier to hit for left-handed batters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] To spare Ruth's eyes, right field—his defensive position—was not pointed into the afternoon sun, as was traditional; left fielder Meusel soon developed headaches from squinting toward home plate.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During the 1923 season, the Yankees were never seriously challenged and won the AL pennant by 17 games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth finished the season with a career-high .393 batting average and 41 home runs, which tied Cy Williams for the most in the major-leagues that year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit a career-high 45 doubles in 1923, and he reached base 379 times, then a major league record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] For the third straight year, the Yankees faced the Giants in the World Series, which Ruth dominated.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He batted .368, walked eight times, scored eight runs, hit three home runs and slugged 1.000 during the series, as the Yankees christened their new stadium with their first World Series championship, four games to two.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1924, the Yankees were favored to become the first team to win four consecutive pennants.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Plagued by injuries, they found themselves in a battle with the Senators.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees won 18 of 22 at one point in September, the Senators beat out the Yankees by two games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .378, winning his only AL batting title, with a league-leading 46 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth did not look like an athlete; he was described as "toothpicks attached to a piano", with a big upper body but thin wrists and legs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had kept up his efforts to stay in shape in 1923 and 1924, but by early 1925 weighed nearly 260 pounds (120 kg).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His annual visit to Hot Springs, Arkansas, where he exercised and took saunas early in the year, did him no good as he spent much of the time carousing in the resort town.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He became ill while there, and relapsed during spring training.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth collapsed in Asheville, North Carolina, as the team journeyed north.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was put on a train for New York, where he was briefly hospitalized.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] A rumor circulated that he had died, prompting British newspapers to print a premature obituary.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In New York, Ruth collapsed again and was found unconscious in his hotel bathroom.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was taken to a hospital where he had multiple convulsions.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] McGeehan wrote that Ruth's illness was due to binging on hot dogs and soda pop before a game, it became known as "the bellyache heard 'round the world".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, the exact cause of his ailment has never been confirmed and remains a mystery.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Glenn Stout, in his history of the Yankees, writes that the Ruth legend is "still one of the most sheltered in sports"; he suggests that alcohol was at the root of Ruth's illness, pointing to the fact that Ruth remained six weeks at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Vincent's Hospital but was allowed to leave, under supervision, for workouts with the team for part of that time.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He concludes that the hospitalization was behavior-related.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Playing just 98 games, Ruth had his worst season as a Yankee; he finished with a .290 average and 25 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished next to last in the AL with a 69–85 record, their last season with a losing record until 1965.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth spent part of the offseason of 1925–26 working out at Artie McGovern's gym, where he got back into shape.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Barrow and Huggins had rebuilt the team and surrounded the veteran core with good young players like Tony Lazzeri and Lou Gehrig, but the Yankees were not expected to win the pennant.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth returned to his normal production during 1926, when he batted .372 with 47 home runs and 146 RBIs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees built a 10-game lead by mid-June and coasted to win the pennant by three games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Louis Cardinals had won the National League with the lowest winning percentage for a pennant winner to that point (.578) and the Yankees were expected to win the World Series easily.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees won the opener in New York, St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In Game Four, Ruth hit three home runs—the first time this had been done in a World Series game—to lead the Yankees to victory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the fifth game, Ruth caught a ball as he crashed into the fence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The play was described by baseball writers as a defensive gem.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] New York took that game, but Grover Cleveland Alexander won Game Six for St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Louis to tie the Series at three games each, then got very drunk.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was nevertheless inserted into Game Seven in the seventh inning and shut down the Yankees to win the game, 3–2, and win the Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had hit his fourth home run of the Series earlier in the game and was the only Yankee to reach base off Alexander; he walked in the ninth inning before being thrown out to end the game when he attempted to steal second base.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth's attempt to steal second is often deemed a baserunning blunder, Creamer pointed out that the Yankees' chances of tying the game would have been greatly improved with a runner in scoring position.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The 1926 World Series was also known for Ruth's promise to Johnny Sylvester, a hospitalized 11-year-old boy.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth promised the child that he would hit a home run on his behalf.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Sylvester had been injured in a fall from a horse, and a friend of Sylvester's father gave the boy two autographed baseballs signed by Yankees and Cardinals.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The friend relayed a promise from Ruth (who did not know the boy) that he would hit a home run for him.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After the Series, Ruth visited the boy in the hospital.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When the matter became public, the press greatly inflated it, and by some accounts, Ruth allegedly saved the boy's life by visiting him, emotionally promising to hit a home run, and doing so.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's 1926 salary of $52,000 was far more than any other baseball player, but he made at least twice as much in other income, including $100,000 from 12 weeks of vaudeville.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The 1927 New York Yankees team is considered one of the greatest squads to ever take the field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Known as Murderers' Row because of the power of its lineup, the team clinched first place on Labor Day, won a then-AL-record 110 games and took the AL pennant by 19 games.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] There was no suspense in the pennant race, and the nation turned its attention to Ruth's pursuit of his own single-season home run record of 59 round trippers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Teammate Lou Gehrig proved to be a slugger who was capable of challenging Ruth for his home run crown; he tied Ruth with 24 home runs late in June.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Through July and August, the dynamic duo was never separated by more than two home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Gehrig took the lead, 45–44, in the first game of a doubleheader at Fenway Park early in September; Ruth responded with two blasts of his own to take the lead, as it proved permanently—Gehrig finished with 47.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Even so, as of September 6, Ruth was still several games off his 1921 pace, and going into the final series against the Senators, had only 57.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He hit two in the first game of the series, including one off of Paul Hopkins, facing his first major league batter, to tie the record.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The following day, September 30, he broke it with his 60th homer, in the eighth inning off Tom Zachary to break a 2–2 tie.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Let's see some son of a bitch try to top that one", Ruth exulted after the game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In addition to his career-high 60 home runs, Ruth batted .356, drove in 164 runs and slugged .772.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the 1927 World Series, the Yankees swept the Pittsburgh Pirates in four games; the National Leaguers were disheartened after watching the Yankees take batting practice before Game One, with ball after ball leaving Forbes Field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] According to Appel, "The 1927 New York Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The following season started off well for the Yankees, who led the league in the early going.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] But the Yankees were plagued by injuries, erratic pitching and inconsistent play.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Philadelphia Athletics, rebuilding after some lean years, erased the Yankees' big lead and even took over first place briefly in early September.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees, however, regained first place when they beat the Athletics three out of four games in a pivotal series at Yankee Stadium later that month, and clinched the pennant in the final weekend of the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's play in 1928 mirrored his team's performance.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He got off to a hot start and on August 1, he had 42 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] This put him ahead of his 60 home run pace from the previous season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He then slumped for the latter part of the season, and he hit just twelve home runs in the last two months.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's batting average also fell to .323, well below his career average.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, he ended the season with 54 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees swept the favored Cardinals in four games in the World Series, with Ruth batting .625 and hitting three home runs in Game Four, including one off Alexander.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Before the 1929 season, Ruppert (who had bought out Huston in 1923) announced that the Yankees would wear uniform numbers to allow fans at cavernous Yankee Stadium to easily identify the players.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Cardinals and Indians had each experimented with uniform numbers; the Yankees were the first to use them on both home and away uniforms.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth batted third and was given number 3.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] According to a long-standing baseball legend, the Yankees adopted their now-iconic pinstriped uniforms in hopes of making Ruth look slimmer.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In truth, though, they had been wearing pinstripes since 1915.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although the Yankees started well, the Athletics soon proved they were the better team in 1929, splitting two series with the Yankees in the first month of the season, then taking advantage of a Yankee losing streak in mid-May to gain first place.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth performed well, the Yankees were not able to catch the Athletics—Connie Mack had built another great team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Tragedy struck the Yankees late in the year when manager Huggins died at 51 of erysipelas, a bacterial skin infection, on September 25, only ten days after he had last directed the team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Despite their past differences, Ruth praised Huggins and described him as a "great guy".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished second, 18 games behind the Athletics.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit .345 during the season, with 46 home runs and 154 RBIs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On October 17, the Yankees hired Bob Shawkey as manager; he was their fourth choice.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had politicked for the job of player-manager, but Ruppert and Barrow never seriously considered him for the position.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Stout deemed this the first hint Ruth would have no future with the Yankees once he retired as a player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Shawkey, a former Yankees player and teammate of Ruth, would prove unable to command Ruth's respect.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On January 7, 1930, salary negotiations between the Yankees and Ruth quickly broke down.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When asked why he thought he was "worth more than the President of the United States," Ruth responded: "Say, if I hadn't been sick last summer, I'd have broken hell out of that home run record!
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Besides, the President gets a four-year contract.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] I'm only asking for three." Exactly two months later, a compromise was reached, with Ruth settling for two years at an unprecedented $80,000 per year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's salary was more than 2.4 times greater than the next-highest salary that season, a record margin as of 2025.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1930, Ruth hit .359 with 49 home runs (his best in his years after 1928) and 153 RBIs, and pitched his first game in nine years, a complete game victory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, the Athletics won their second consecutive pennant and World Series, as the Yankees finished in third place, sixteen games back.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] At the end of the season, Shawkey was fired and replaced with Cubs manager Joe McCarthy, though Ruth again unsuccessfully sought the job.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] McCarthy was a disciplinarian, but chose not to interfere with Ruth, who did not seek conflict with the manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The team improved in 1931, but was no match for the Athletics, who won 107 games, 13+1⁄2 games in front of the Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth, for his part, hit .373, with 46 home runs and 163 RBIs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the 1932 season, the Yankees went 107–47 and won the pennant.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's effectiveness had decreased somewhat, but he still hit .341 with 41 home runs and 137 RBIs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Nevertheless, he was sidelined twice because of injuries during the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees faced the Cubs, McCarthy's former team, in the 1932 World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] There was bad blood between the two teams as the Yankees resented the Cubs only awarding half a World Series share to Mark Koenig, a former Yankee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The games at Yankee Stadium had not been sellouts; both were won by the home team, with Ruth collecting two singles, but scoring four runs as he was walked four times by the Cubs pitchers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In Chicago, Ruth was resentful at the hostile crowds that met the Yankees' train and jeered them at the hotel.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The crowd for Game Three included New York Governor Franklin D.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Roosevelt, the Democratic candidate for president, who sat with Chicago Mayor Anton Cermak.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Many in the crowd threw lemons at Ruth, a sign of derision, and others (as well as the Cubs themselves) shouted abuse at Ruth and other Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They were briefly silenced when Ruth hit a three-run home run off Charlie Root in the first inning, but soon revived, and the Cubs tied the score at 4–4 in the fourth inning, partly due to Ruth's fielding error in the outfield.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When Ruth came to the plate in the top of the fifth, the Chicago crowd and players, led by pitcher Guy Bush, were screaming insults at Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] With the count at two balls and one strike, Ruth gestured, possibly in the direction of center field, and after the next pitch (a strike), may have pointed there with one hand.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth hit the fifth pitch over the center field fence; estimates were that it traveled nearly 500 feet (150 m).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Whether or not Ruth intended to indicate where he planned to (and did) hit the ball (Charlie Devens, who, in 1999, was interviewed as Ruth's surviving teammate in that game, did not think so), the incident has gone down in legend as Babe Ruth's called shot.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees won Game Three, and the following day clinched the Series with another victory.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During that game, Bush hit Ruth on the arm with a pitch, causing words to be exchanged and provoking a game-winning Yankee rally.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He batted .301, with 34 home runs, 103 RBIs, and a league-leading 114 walks, as the Yankees finished in second place, seven games behind the Senators.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Athletics manager Connie Mack selected him to play right field in the first Major League Baseball All-Star Game, held on July 6, 1933, at Comiskey Park in Chicago.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He hit the first home run in the All-Star Game's history, a two-run blast against Bill Hallahan during the third inning, which helped the AL win the game 4–2.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During the final game of the 1933 season, as a publicity stunt organized by his team, Ruth was called upon and pitched a complete game victory against the Red Sox, his final appearance as a pitcher.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Despite unremarkable pitching numbers, Ruth had a 5–0 record in five games for the Yankees, raising his career totals to 94–46.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1934, Ruth played in his last full season with the Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By this time, years of high living were starting to catch up with him.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His conditioning had deteriorated to the point that he could no longer field or run.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He accepted a pay cut to $35,000 from Ruppert, but he was still the highest-paid player in the major leagues.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He could still handle a bat, recording a .288 batting average with 22 home runs, and on July 13, 1934, he hit his 700th career home run.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, Reisler described these statistics as "merely mortal" by Ruth's previous standards.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was selected to the AL All-Star team for the second consecutive year, even though he was in the twilight of his career.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During the game, New York Giants pitcher Carl Hubbell struck out Ruth and four other future Hall-of-Famers consecutively.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Yankees finished second again, seven games behind the Tigers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By this time, Ruth knew he was nearly finished as a player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He desired to remain in baseball as a manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was often spoken of as a possible candidate as managerial jobs opened up, but in 1932, when he was mentioned as a contender for the Red Sox position, Ruth stated that he was not yet ready to leave the field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] There were rumors that Ruth was a likely candidate each time when the Cleveland Indians, Cincinnati Reds, and Detroit Tigers were looking for a manager, but nothing came of them.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Just before the 1934 season, Ruppert offered to make Ruth the manager of the Yankees' top minor-league team, the Newark Bears, but he was talked out of it by his wife, Claire, and his business manager, Christy Walsh.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Tigers owner Frank Navin seriously considered acquiring Ruth and making him player-manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, Ruth insisted on delaying the meeting until he came back from a trip to Hawaii.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth opted to go on his trip, despite Barrow advising him that he was making a mistake; in any event, Ruth's asking price was too high for the notoriously tight-fisted Navin.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Tigers' job ultimately went to Mickey Cochrane.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Early in the 1934 season, Ruth made no secret of his desire to manage the Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, that job was never a serious possibility.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert always supported McCarthy, who would remain in his position for another 12 seasons.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The relationship between Ruth and McCarthy had been lukewarm at best, and Ruth's open campaigning to replace him further chilled their interpersonal relations.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By the end of the season, Ruth hinted that he would retire unless Ruppert named him manager of the Yankees.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When the time came, Ruppert wanted Ruth to leave the team without drama or hard feelings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During the 1934–35 offseason, Ruth circled the world with his wife; the trip included a barnstorming tour of the Far East.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] At his final stop in the United Kingdom before returning home, Ruth was introduced to cricket by Australian player Alan Fairfax, and after having little luck in a cricketer's stance, he stood as a baseball batter and launched some massive shots around the field, destroying the bat in the process.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although Fairfax regretted that he could not have the time to make Ruth a cricket player, Ruth had lost any interest in such a career upon learning that the best batsmen made only about $40 per week.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Also during the offseason, Ruppert had been sounding out the other clubs in hopes of finding one that would be willing to take Ruth as a manager or player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, the only serious offer came from Athletics owner-manager Connie Mack, who gave some thought to stepping down as manager in favor of Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] However, Mack later dropped the idea, saying that Ruth's wife would be running the team in a month if Ruth ever took over.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] While the barnstorming tour was underway, Ruppert began negotiating with Boston Braves owner Judge Emil Fuchs, who wanted Ruth as a gate attraction.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Braves had enjoyed modest recent success, finishing fourth in the National League in both 1933 and 1934, but the team drew poorly at the box office.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Unable to afford the rent at Braves Field, Fuchs had considered holding dog races there when the Braves were not at home, only to be turned down by Landis.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After a series of phone calls, letters, and meetings, the Yankees traded Ruth to the Braves on February 26, 1935.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert had stated that he would not release Ruth to go to another team as a full-time player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] For this reason, it was announced that Ruth would become a team vice president and would be consulted on all club transactions, in addition to playing.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was also made assistant manager to Braves skipper Bill McKechnie.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In a long letter to Ruth a few days before the press conference, Fuchs promised Ruth a share in the Braves' profits, with the possibility of becoming co-owner of the team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Fuchs also raised the possibility of Ruth succeeding McKechnie as manager, perhaps as early as 1936.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruppert called the deal "the greatest opportunity Ruth ever had".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] There was considerable attention as Ruth reported for spring training.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He did not hit his first home run of the spring until after the team had left Florida, and was beginning the road north in Savannah.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He hit two in an exhibition game against the Bears.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Amid much press attention, Ruth played his first home game in Boston in over 16 years.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Before an opening-day crowd of over 25,000, including five of New England's six state governors, Ruth accounted for all the Braves' runs in a 4–2 win over the New York Giants, hitting a two-run home run, singling to drive in a third run and later in the inning scoring the fourth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although age and weight had slowed him, he made a running catch in left field that sportswriters deemed the defensive highlight of the game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth had two hits in the second game of the season, but it quickly went downhill both for him and the Braves from there.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The season soon settled down to a routine of Ruth performing poorly on the few occasions he even played at all.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] As April passed into May, Ruth's physical deterioration became even more pronounced.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] While he remained productive at the plate early on, he could do little else.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His conditioning had become so poor that he could barely trot around the bases.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He made so many errors that three Braves pitchers told McKechnie they would not take the mound if he was in the lineup.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Before long, Ruth stopped hitting as well.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He grew increasingly annoyed that McKechnie ignored most of his advice.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] McKechnie later said that Ruth's presence made enforcing discipline nearly impossible.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth soon realized that Fuchs had deceived him, and had no intention of making him manager or giving him any significant off-field duties.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He later said his only duties as vice president consisted of making public appearances and autographing tickets.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth also found out that far from giving him a share of the profits, Fuchs wanted him to invest some of *his* money in the team in a last-ditch effort to improve its balance sheet.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] As it turned out, Fuchs and Ruppert had both known all along that Ruth's non-playing positions were meaningless.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By the end of the first month of the season, Ruth concluded he was finished even as a part-time player.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] As early as May 12, he asked Fuchs to let him retire.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ultimately, Fuchs persuaded Ruth to remain at least until after the Memorial Day doubleheader in Philadelphia.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the interim was a western road trip, at which the rival teams had scheduled days to honor him.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Louis, Ruth performed poorly, and his batting average sank to .155, with only two additional home runs for a total of three on the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In the first two games in Pittsburgh, Ruth had only one hit, though a long fly caught by Paul Waner probably would have been a home run in any other ballpark besides Forbes Field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth played in the third game of the Pittsburgh series on May 25, 1935, and added one more tale to his playing legend.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth went 4-for-4, including three home runs, though the Braves lost the game 11–7.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The last two were off Ruth's old Cubs nemesis, Guy Bush.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The final home run, both of the game and of Ruth's career, sailed out of the park over the right field upper deck–the first time anyone had hit a fair ball completely out of Forbes Field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was urged to make this his last game, but he had given his word to Fuchs to stay on through Memorial Day and played in Cincinnati and Philadelphia.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The first game of the doubleheader in Philadelphia—the Braves lost both—would be his final major league appearance.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth retired on June 2 after an argument with Fuchs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He finished 1935 with a .181 average—easily his worst as a full-time position player—and the final six of his 714 home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The Braves, 10–27 when Ruth left, finished 38–115, at .248 the worst winning percentage in modern National League history.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Insolvent like his team, Fuchs gave up control of the Braves before the end of the season; the National League took over the franchise at the end of the year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] At the time of his retirement, Ruth held many baseball batting records.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] These include the career records for home runs (714), slugging percentage (0.690), runs batted in (2,213), bases on balls (2,062) and on-base percentage (.474).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He still remains in the top ten of many statistical rankings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although Fuchs had given Ruth his unconditional release, no major league team expressed an interest in hiring him in any capacity.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth still hoped to be hired as a manager if he could not play anymore, but only one managerial position, Cleveland, became available between Ruth's retirement and the end of the 1937 season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Asked if he had considered Ruth for the job, Indians owner Alva Bradley replied negatively.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Of the five members in the inaugural class of Baseball Hall of Fame in 1936 (Ty Cobb, Honus Wagner, Christy Mathewson, Walter Johnson and Ruth), only Ruth was not given an offer to manage a baseball team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The author believed there was not necessarily a relationship between personal conduct and managerial success, noting that John McGraw, Billy Martin, and Bobby Valentine were winners despite character flaws.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth played much golf and in a few exhibition baseball games, where he demonstrated a continuing ability to draw large crowds.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] This appeal contributed to the Dodgers hiring him as first base coach in 1938.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] When Ruth was hired, Brooklyn general manager Larry MacPhail made it clear that Ruth would not be considered for the manager's job if, as expected, Burleigh Grimes retired at the end of the season.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although much was said about what Ruth could teach the younger players, in practice, his duties were to appear on the field in uniform and encourage base runners—he was not called upon to relay signs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In August, shortly before the baseball rosters expanded, Ruth sought an opportunity to return as an active player in a pinch hitting role.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth often took batting practice before games and felt that he could take on the limited role.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Grimes denied his request, citing Ruth's poor vision in his right eye, his inability to run the bases, and the risk of an injury to Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth got along well with everyone except team captain Leo Durocher, who was hired as Grimes' replacement at season's end.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth then left his job as a first base coach and would never again work in any capacity in the game of baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On July 4, 1939, Ruth spoke on Lou Gehrig Appreciation Day at Yankee Stadium as members of the 1927 Yankees and a sellout crowd turned out to honor the first baseman, who was forced into premature retirement by ALS, which would kill him two years later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The next week, Ruth went to Cooperstown, New York, for the formal opening of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Three years earlier, he was one of the first five players elected to the hall.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] As radio broadcasts of baseball games became popular, Ruth sought a job in that field, arguing that his celebrity and knowledge of baseball would assure large audiences, but he received no offers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] During World War II, he made many personal appearances to advance the war effort, including his last appearance as a player at Yankee Stadium, in a 1943 exhibition for the Army-Navy Relief Fund.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He hit a long fly ball off Walter Johnson; the blast left the field, curving foul, but Ruth circled the bases anyway.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1946, he made a final effort to gain a job in baseball when he contacted new Yankees boss MacPhail, but he was sent a rejection letter.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1999, Ruth's granddaughter, Linda Tosetti, and his daughter, Julia Ruth Stevens, said that Babe's inability to land a managerial role with the Yankees caused him to feel hurt and slump into a severe depression.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth started playing golf when he was 20 and continued playing the game throughout his life.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His appearance at many New York courses drew spectators and headlines.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Rye Golf Club was among the courses he played with teammate Lyn Lary in June 1933.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] With birdies on 3 holes, Ruth posted the best score.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In retirement, he became one of the first celebrity golfers participating in charity tournaments, including one where he was pitted against Ty Cobb.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth met Helen Woodford, by some accounts, in a coffee shop in Boston, where she was a waitress.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They married as teenagers on October 17, 1914.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Although Ruth later claimed to have been married in Elkton, Maryland, records show that they were married at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Paul's Catholic Church in Ellicott City.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They adopted a daughter, Dorothy, in 1921.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth and Helen separated around 1925 reportedly because of Ruth's repeated infidelities and neglect.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They appeared in public as a couple for the last time during the 1926 World Series.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Helen died in January 1929 at age 31 in a fire in a house in Watertown, Massachusetts owned by Edward Kinder, a dentist with whom she had been living as "Mrs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In her book, *My Dad, the Babe*, Dorothy claimed that she was Ruth's biological child by a mistress named Juanita Jennings.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1980, Juanita, who was at the time very ill, admitted this to Dorothy and Dorothy's sister, Julia.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On April 17, 1929, three months after the death of his first wife, Ruth married actress and model Claire Merritt Hodgson and adopted her daughter Julia.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] It was the second and final marriage for both parties.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Claire was well-travelled and educated, and put structure into Ruth's life, like Miller Huggins did for him on the field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By one account, Julia and Dorothy were, through no fault of their own, the reason for the seven-year rift in Ruth's relationship with teammate Lou Gehrig.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Sometime in 1932, during a conversation that she assumed was private, Gehrig's mother remarked, "It's a shame [Claire] doesn't dress Dorothy as nicely as she dresses her own daughter." When the comment got back to Ruth, he angrily told Gehrig to tell his mother to mind her own business.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Gehrig, in turn, took offense at what he perceived as Ruth's comment about his mother.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The two men reportedly never spoke off the field until they reconciled at Yankee Stadium on Lou Gehrig Appreciation Day, July 4, 1939, shortly after Gehrig's retirement from baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They're too much fun." A detective that the Yankees hired to follow him one night in Chicago reported that Ruth had been with six women.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ping Bodie said that he was not Ruth's roommate while traveling; "I room with his suitcase".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Before the start of the 1922 season, Ruth had signed a three-year contract at $52,000 per year (equivalent to $1,000,000 in 2025) with an option to renew for two additional years.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His performance during the 1922 season had been disappointing, attributed in part to his drinking and late-night hours.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After the end of the 1922 season, he was asked to sign a contract addendum with a morals clause.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth and Ruppert signed it on November 11, 1922.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] It called for Ruth to abstain entirely from the use of intoxicating liquors, and to not stay up later than 1:00 a.m. during the training and playing season without permission of the manager.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth was also enjoined from any action or misbehavior that would compromise his ability to play baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1928, Ruth campaigned for Democratic U.S. presidential nominee Al Smith.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] As early as the war years, doctors had cautioned Ruth to take better care of his health, and he grudgingly followed their advice, limiting his drinking and not going on a proposed trip to support the troops in the South Pacific.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1946, Ruth began experiencing severe pain over his left eye and had difficulty swallowing.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In November 1946, Ruth entered French Hospital in New York for tests, which revealed that he had an inoperable malignant tumor at the base of his skull and in his neck.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The malady was a lesion known as nasopharyngeal carcinoma, or lymphoepithelioma.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] A physician who reviewed Ruth's autopsy in 1998 concluded that Ruth's lifelong use of tobacco "probably played a part" in his cancer.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His name and fame gave him access to experimental treatments, and he was one of the first cancer patients to receive both drugs and radiation treatment simultaneously.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Having lost 80 pounds (36 kg), he was discharged from the hospital in February and went to Florida to recuperate.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He returned to New York and Yankee Stadium after the season started.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The new commissioner, Happy Chandler (Judge Landis had died in 1944), proclaimed April 27, 1947, Babe Ruth Day around the major leagues, with the most significant observance to be at Yankee Stadium.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] A number of teammates and others spoke in honor of Ruth, who briefly addressed the crowd of almost 60,000.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By then, his voice was a soft whisper with a very low, raspy tone.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Around this time, developments in chemotherapy offered some hope for Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The doctors had not told Ruth he had cancer because of his family's fear that he might do himself harm.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] They treated him with pterolyl triglutamate (Teropterin), a folic acid derivative; he may have been the first human subject.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth showed dramatic improvement during the summer of 1947, so much so that his case was presented by his doctors at a scientific meeting, without using his name.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was able to travel around the country, doing promotional work for the Ford Motor Company on American Legion Baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He appeared again at another day in his honor at Yankee Stadium in September, but was not well enough to pitch in an old-timers game as he had hoped.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The improvement was only a temporary remission, and by late 1947, Ruth was unable to help with the writing of his autobiography, *The Babe Ruth Story*, which was almost entirely ghostwritten.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In and out of the hospital in Manhattan, he left for Florida in February 1948, doing what activities he could.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] After six weeks he returned to New York to appear at a book-signing party.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He also traveled to California to witness the filming of the movie based on the book.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On June 5, 1948, a "gaunt and hollowed-out" Ruth visited Yale University to donate a manuscript of *The Babe Ruth Story* to its library.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] At Yale, he met with future president George H.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Bush, who was the captain of the Yale baseball team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On June 13, Ruth visited Yankee Stadium for the final time in his life, appearing at the 25th-anniversary celebrations of "The House that Ruth Built".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] By this time he had lost much weight and had difficulty walking.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Introduced along with his surviving teammates from 1923, Ruth used a bat as a cane.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Nat Fein's photo of Ruth taken from behind, standing near home plate and facing "Ruthville" (right field) became one of baseball's most famous and widely circulated photographs, and won the Pulitzer Prize.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth made one final trip on behalf of American Legion Baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He then entered Memorial Hospital, where he would die.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was never told he had cancer; however, before his death, he surmised it.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He was able to leave the hospital for a few short trips, including a final visit to Baltimore.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On July 26, 1948, Ruth left the hospital to attend the premiere of the film *The Babe Ruth Story*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Shortly thereafter, he returned to the hospital for the final time.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's condition gradually grew worse, and only a few visitors were permitted to see him, one of whom was National League president and future Commissioner of Baseball Ford C.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] He had been such a big man and his arms were just skinny little bones, and his face was so haggard", Frick said years later.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Thousands of New Yorkers, including many children, stood vigil outside the hospital during Ruth's final days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On August 16, 1948, at 8:01 p.m., Ruth died in his sleep at the age of 53.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His funeral service took place over three days.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His open casket was placed on display in the rotunda of Yankee Stadium, where it remained for two days; 77,000 people filed past to pay him tribute.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] His Requiem Mass was celebrated by Francis Cardinal Spellman at St.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Patrick's Cathedral; a crowd estimated at 75,000 waited outside.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth is buried with his second wife, Claire, on a hillside in Section 25 at the Gate of Heaven Cemetery in Hawthorne, New York.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] On April 19, 1949, the Yankees unveiled a granite monument in Ruth's honor in center field of Yankee Stadium.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The monument was located in the field of play next to a flagpole and similar tributes to Huggins and Gehrig until the stadium was remodeled from 1974 to 1975, which resulted in the outfield fences moving inward and enclosing the monuments from the playing field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] This area was known thereafter as Monument Park.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Yankee Stadium, "the House that Ruth Built", was replaced after the 2008 season with a new Yankee Stadium across the street from the old one; Monument Park was subsequently moved to the new venue behind the center field fence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's uniform number 3 has been retired by the Yankees, and he is one of five Yankees players or managers to have a granite monument within the stadium.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] In 1974, Ruth's birthplace in Baltimore was renovated and opened to the public as the Babe Ruth Birthplace and Museum.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] The museum houses a collection of artifacts from Ruth's life, including some rare baseball cards and the earliest known signature of Ruth, from when he was still pitching in the schoolyard.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p03] Ruth's widow, Claire, his two daughters, Dorothy and Julia, and his sister, Mamie, helped select and install exhibits for the museum.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth was the first baseball star to be the subject of overwhelming public adulation.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Baseball had been known for star players such as Ty Cobb and "Shoeless Joe" Jackson, but both men had uneasy relations with fans.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In Cobb's case, the incidents were sometimes marked by violence.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth's biographers agreed that he benefited from the timing of his ascension to "Home Run King".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The country had been hit hard by both the war and the 1918 flu pandemic and longed for something to help put these traumas behind it.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth also resonated in a country which felt, in the aftermath of the war, that it took second place to no one.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Montville argued that Ruth was a larger-than-life figure who was capable of unprecedented athletic feats in the nation's largest city.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth became an icon of the social changes that marked the early 1920s.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In his history of the Yankees, Glenn Stout writes that "Ruth was New York incarnate—uncouth and raw, flamboyant and flashy, oversized, out of scale, and absolutely unstoppable".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] During his lifetime, Ruth became a symbol of the United States.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] During World War II, Japanese soldiers yelled in English, "To hell with Babe Ruth", to anger American soldiers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth replied that he hoped "every Jap that mention[ed] my name gets shot".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Creamer recorded that "Babe Ruth transcended sport and moved far beyond the artificial limits of baselines and outfield fences and sports pages".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Wagenheim stated, "He appealed to a deeply rooted American yearning for the definitive climax: clean, quick, unarguable." According to Glenn Stout, "Ruth's home runs were [an] exalted, uplifting experience that meant more to fans than any runs they were responsible for.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Although Ruth was not just a power hitter—he was the Yankees' best bunter, and an excellent outfielder—Ruth's penchant for hitting home runs altered how baseball is played.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Prior to 1920, home runs were unusual, and managers tried to win games by getting a runner on base and bringing him around to score through such means as the stolen base, the bunt, and the hit and run.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Advocates of what was dubbed "inside baseball", such as Giants manager McGraw, disliked the home run, considering it a blot on the purity of the game.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Phelon, after the 1920 season, Ruth's breakout performance that season and the response in excitement and attendance, "settled, for all time to come, that the American public is nuttier over the Home Run than the Clever Fielding or the Hitless Pitching.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] According to sportswriter Grantland Rice, only two sports figures of the 1920s approached Ruth in popularity—boxer Jack Dempsey and racehorse Man o' War.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] One of the factors that contributed to Ruth's broad appeal was the uncertainty about his family and early life.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth appeared to exemplify the American success story, that even an uneducated, unsophisticated youth, without any family wealth or connections, can do something better than anyone else in the world.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Montville writes that "the fog [surrounding his childhood] will make him forever accessible, universal.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] He will be the patron saint of American possibility." Similarly, the fact that Ruth played in the pre-television era, when a relatively small portion of his fans had the opportunity to see him play, allowed his legend to grow through word of mouth and the hyperbole of sports reporters.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Reisler states that recent sluggers who surpassed Ruth's 60-home run mark, such as Mark McGwire and Barry Bonds, generated much less excitement than when Ruth repeatedly broke the single-season home run record in the 1920s.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Ruth dominated a relatively small sports world, while Americans of the present era have many sports available to watch.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Thomas Barthel describes Ruth as one of the first celebrity athletes; numerous biographies have portrayed him as "larger than life".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] A dominant figure in a field is often referred to as "the Babe Ruth" of that field.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] He was the first athlete to make more money from endorsements and off-the-field activities than from his sport.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 2006, Montville stated that more books have been written about Ruth than any other member of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The long ball era that Ruth started continues in baseball: owners build ballparks to encourage home runs.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In various rankings, Ruth has been named the greatest baseball player of all time.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 1998, *The Sporting News* ranked him number one on the list of "Baseball's 100 Greatest Players".
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 1999, baseball fans named Ruth to the Major League Baseball All-Century Team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] He was named baseball's Greatest Player Ever in a 1969 ballot.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The Associated Press reported in 1993 that Muhammad Ali was tied with Babe Ruth as the most recognized athlete in America.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 1999, the Associated Press named Ruth the greatest athlete of the 20th century, while an ESPN poll ranked him the second-greatest North American athlete of the century.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 1983, the United States Postal Service honored Ruth with a twenty-cent stamp.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 2022, *The Sporting News* named Ruth on their "New York Mount Rushmore of Sports", while ESPN ranked him as the greatest baseball player ever that same year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Several of the most expensive items of sports memorabilia ever sold at auction are associated with Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The jersey Ruth wore when hitting his "called shot" home run in the 1932 World Series sold in 2024 for a record $24 million.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] A Ruth 1920 Yankees jersey that sold for $4.4 million in 2012 (equivalent to $6.2 million in 2025) was, for several years, one of the most expensive piece of sports memorabilia ever sold.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The bat with which he hit the first home run at Yankee Stadium is in *The Guinness Book of World Records* as the most expensive baseball bat sold at auction, having fetched $1.265 million in 2004 (equivalent to $2.1563 million in 2025).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] Other bats used by Ruth sold for $1.6 million in 2022 and $1.85 million in 2023.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] A hat of Ruth's from the 1934 season set a record for a baseball cap when David Wells sold it at auction for $537 thousand in 2012.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 2017, Charlie Sheen sold Ruth's 1927 World Series ring for $2 million, a record for a championship ring.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] One lasting legacy of the craze over Ruth may be the Baby Ruth candy bar.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The original company to market the confectionery, the Curtiss Candy Company, maintained that the bar was named after Ruth Cleveland, daughter of president Grover Cleveland.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] She died in 1904 and the bar was first marketed in 1921, at the height of the craze over Ruth.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] He later sought to market candy bearing his name; he was refused a trademark because of the Baby Ruth bar.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] The Ruth estate licensed his likeness for use in an advertising campaign for Baby Ruth in 1995.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 2005, Baby Ruth became the official candy bar of Major League Baseball.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/babe-ruth-p04] In 2018, Ruth was posthumously awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President Donald Trump; his grandson Tom Stevens accepted the award on his behalf.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The **Baseball Writers' Association of America** (**BBWAA**) is a professional association for journalists writing about Major League Baseball for daily newspapers, magazines, and qualifying websites.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization was founded in 1908 and is known for its annual awards and voting on membership in the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization began with 43 founding members.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Jackson, who became the association's first president.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] At that time, Jackson was the sporting editor (today called *sports editor*) of the *Detroit Free Press*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Also selected as officers were Irving E.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Sanborn of the *Chicago Tribune*, syndicated columnist Hugh Fullerton, and *The Boston Globe* baseball writer Tim Murnane.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] A second meeting was held in New York City in December; Sanborn decided he could not serve as an officer at that time, and he was replaced by William Weart of the *Philadelphia Times*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The slate of officers was ratified, and anyone who wrote about baseball in major league cities was eligible for membership.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] This policy changed, however, in December 1913, at which time it was decided that minor-league baseball writers could also become members.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Then, Jackson became a dominant force in the early years of the baseball writers, being elected as president of the association during nine consecutive terms.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Jackson finally retired in 1919, while Sanborn returned to assume the position of president.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] After that, Jackson became a member of the BBWAA Board of Directors.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The organization's primary function is to work with Major League Baseball and individual teams to assure clubhouse and press-box access for BBWAA members.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In addition, BBWAA members also elect players to the National Baseball Hall of Fame, which is the organization's most public function.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] All writers with 10 continuous years of membership in the BBWAA, plus active BBWAA membership at any time in the preceding 10 years, are eligible to vote for the Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The BBWAA also votes annually for the Most Valuable Player Award, Cy Young Award, Jackie Robinson Rookie of the Year Award, and Manager of the Year Award in each of the two major leagues.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The Hall of Fame also empowers the BBWAA's Historical Overview Committee, made up of 11 or 12 veteran BBWAA members, to formulate the annual ballot for the Veterans Committee.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Considering the ready availability of television broadcasts for the majority of baseball games, plus instant access to information through the Internet, some have called into question why the BBWAA has not broadened its membership rules to include broadcasters and researchers.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Others have openly questioned why the BBWAA is involved in the award and Hall of Fame voting processes at all, citing in some cases journalistic integrity and the need to remain unbiased in their coverage of newsworthy events.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The BBWAA's most public function is to annually vote on candidates for the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In or about 2000, the BBWAA took over the voting responsibility for the Edgar Martínez Award, given each year to the outstanding designated hitter in the American League.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] From 1953 to 1962, the BBWAA presented a "Sophomore of the Year Award" in each league.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] In 1997, a 36-member BBWAA panel selected the Major League Baseball All-Time Team.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] The annual BBWAA Career Excellence Award is the highest award given by the BBWAA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Taylor Spink, longtime publisher of *The Sporting News*, it was named the J.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Taylor Spink Award until adopting its current name in February 2021.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] It has been awarded annually for "meritorious contributions to baseball writing", except for one year during the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] Recipients are not considered members of the National Baseball Hall of Fame but are permanently recognized in an exhibit at the Hall's library.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] For information about the chapter and its presiding officer, see footnote and Red Foley (past chairman).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/baseball-writers-association-of-america] For a list of presidents and secretaries from 1908 to the present, see footnote During the 2012 World Series, the Association elected its first female president, Susan Slusser, of the *San Francisco Chronicle*.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] The **BBWAA Career Excellence Award**, formerly the **J.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Taylor Spink Award**, is the highest award given by the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] It is given "for meritorious contributions to baseball writing" and voted on annually by the BBWAA.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Winners are typically announced in December, with the award presented at the Baseball Hall of Fame in July.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Frick Award for baseball broadcasting, the honorees are permanently recognized in a "Scribes & Mikemen" exhibit in the Hall's library.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] The award was instituted in 1962 and named after J.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Taylor Spink, publisher of *The Sporting News* from 1914 to 1962, and the award's first recipient.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] The honoree does not have to be a member of the Baseball Writers' Association of America (BBWAA), but every recipient from the award's 1962 inception through 2013 had been a BBWAA member at some time.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] The first recipient who had never been a BBWAA member was 2014 recipient Roger Angell.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Despite having written on baseball for more than a half-century, Angell never worked a specific baseball writing beat, thereby making him ineligible for BBWAA membership.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] For several years in the early 2000s, honorees became life members of the Veterans Committee, which elects players whose eligibility for BBWAA consideration has ended, and is also the sole body that elects non-players for induction into the Hall.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Starting with elections for induction in 2008, voting on the main Veterans Committee, which then selected only players whose careers began in 1943 or later, was restricted to Hall of Fame members.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] After further changes announced for the 2011 and 2017 elections, BBWAA Career Excellence Award winners are eligible to serve on all of the era-based voting bodies that succeeded the Veterans Committee (and are still colloquially referred to as such).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Through 2006, the BBWAA designated honorees based on the *announcement* year (typically in December).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] In the below table, winners through 2006 are listed with both their announcement year, and their induction *ceremony* year (the ensuing summer).
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] In 2007, the BBWAA changed the year designation for the award to coincide with the induction ceremony.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Thus, while the official BBWAA year designations jump from 2006 to 2008, the award has been bestowed annually since inception, except for one year missed due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] From 1972 through 1981, there were multiple honorees each year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Since that time, there has been a single winner each year.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Through 2010, the award was presented during the actual induction ceremony; since then, it has been presented at the Hall of Fame awards presentation, held the day before the induction ceremony.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] In recent years, the Hall of Fame has announced the finalists for the award and final vote totals.
[src:baseball-writers-association-of-america/bbwaa-career-excellence-award] Previously, such detail was not made public, with only the winner announced.
